<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the value added tax administration between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">The presented material informs about the course and results of parallel inspections performed by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on value added tax administration and the use of VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System). on value added tax).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so revenues from value added tax affect not only the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">The parallel inspections focused mainly on the control of the procedure of tax administrators in verifying the amount of value added tax paid in business transactions carried out between individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of value added tax payers in the individual Member States of the European Union and on the commercial transactions carried out by these payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the data in the VIES system and the data in the value added tax return filed by the payer should alert the tax administrator to suspicious cases and enable the detection of tax evasion or under water.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit of the performed parallel inspections consisted not only in the exchange of information on the progress of financial resp. tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular in verifying the use of the VIES system in controlling the exercise of the right to exemption from value added tax in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained during the implementation of parallel inspections is beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of other parallel inspections in cooperation with the inspection institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the value added tax administration for the period from 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Inspection number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of control: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and fulfillment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">On 12 September 2005, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SAO, CR”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SAO SR”) concluded an Agreement on Cooperation in Audit Activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the agreement was cooperation in parallel control actions "Value Added Tax Administration", included in the plan of control activities of the SAO, CR for 2005 under No. 05/19 and "Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and recovery of value added tax". and fulfillment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU member states ”, included in the SAO SR plan of control activities under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel control actions had the character of a coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated inspection was processed in accordance with the European Implementing Regulation No. 31 for INTOSAI inspection standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent specified in the concluded contract and in the preparation of a joint final report on the result of parallel inspections.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated inspection was to verify selected cases of delivery and acquisition of goods in suspicious business transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter "CR") and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter "SR").</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties have contractually agreed to provide each other with information from public sources, from the electronic system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on received and sent requests to verify business transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="21">The inspections were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by the Department of the State Budget and the Territorial Departments of Central Bohemia, Northwestern Bohemia, Southern Bohemia, Southern Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The auditees were the Ministry of Finance and 12 tax offices: the Financial Office in Mladá Boleslav, the Financial Office in Kolín, the Financial Office in Teplice, the Financial Office in Karlovy Vary, the Financial Office in Tábor, the Financial Office in Brno III, the Financial Office in Znojmo, the Financial Office in Zlín, the Financial Office in Šumperk, the Financial Office Ostrava I, the Financial Office for Prague 7 and the Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic was performed by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: Bratislava I Tax Office, Komárno Tax Office, Trenčín Tax Office, Prievidza Tax Office, Zvolen Tax Office, Tax Office Dolný Kubín Office, Košice II Tax Office, Košice V Tax Office and Michalovce Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of inspections:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel control actions was to check the progress of financial, resp. tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") after the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter "EU") and examine the use of electronic information system VIES, especially in monitoring the .</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited period of the coordinated inspection was the period from 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel inspections In the EU Member States, the electronic VIES system is in place, which allows tax administrations to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt taxable supplies from VAT and in the country of destination to verify that the purchaser duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES is not centralized within the EU, each Member State is developing its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The inspection revealed differences in the national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The summary reports show the values ​​of deliveries of goods to other EU Member States, the values ​​of the services provided are not reported in the summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from summary reports submitted by Czech taxpayers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of tax authorities, where they are compared with data on deliveries of goods to other EU Member States stated in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit the data from the summary reports to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In the Slovak Republic, data from summary reports submitted by Slovak taxpayers at tax offices are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, taxpayers report the value of supplies of goods and the value of services provided to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT returns, which allows comparing the values ​​stated in summary reports with the values ​​of supplies of goods under VAT returns and identifying any differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Slovak Republic, the values ​​of goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are reported in aggregate on a common line of the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, in the Slovak Republic, the system does not allow automatic identification of differences between the values ​​of the supply of goods according to VAT tax returns and summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the values ​​of supplies of goods in VAT tax returns makes it possible to use the results of comparing data when checking the exemption of supplies of goods to the EU from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="39">Delivered data from summary reports submitted by payers in other EU member states are processed at CLO and compared with the value of acquisition of goods stated by payers from the Czech Republic, resp. SR in tax returns for VAT.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the Slovak Republic, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax administrators themselves decide which cases of differences they will examine.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values ​​of deliveries and acquisitions of goods must be checked by the tax administrator, and forwards the list of these cases to the locally competent tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that for the most significant deviations, it will be checked whether the VAT was declared in the correct amount when purchasing the goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also drew attention to some problems in the VAT administration system of complications caused by different reporting of intra-Community transactions (ie supplies and acquisitions of goods by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Aggregate reports are submitted in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum deadline for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the respective quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Reducing the period for which recapitulative statements are submitted to one month, together with shortening the processing time, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">Tax administrations would thus be able to verify more effectively whether VAT on intra-Community acquisitions was declared at the correct level.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, filing VAT returns and recapitulative statements for the same tax period (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer reported the same value of supplies of goods to the EU in both the recapitulative statement and the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">Differences between the values ​​of delivery of goods reported by payers from the EU and the values ​​of acquisition of goods reported by payers from the Czech Republic, resp. The Slovak Republic was caused, among other things, by different reporting of data on intra-Community supply and acquisition in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the inclusion of received advances in the recapitulative statements, or the reporting of intra-Community supplies in the supplier's recapitulative statement in a quarter other than intra-Community acquisitions in the acquirer's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">Unification of the conditions for reporting this data within the EU would lead to more efficient control activities of the tax administrations of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation between the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic was also focused on the examination of selected intra-Community transactions carried out between the two states.</seg>
<seg id="52">A total of 40 cases of business transactions carried out between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax subjects were examined, in which there were doubts about their execution, resp. suspicion of VAT evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR found the following facts, among others:</seg>
<seg id="54">taxable persons have declared in their VAT returns for the purpose of unauthorized acquisition of an excessive VAT deduction the execution of intra-Community transactions which have not actually taken place;</seg>
<seg id="55">the taxable persons reported intra-Community supplies in the context of carousel transactions, in which there was an intentional multiple reduction in the value of supplies in order to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers reported in their VAT returns and recapitulative statements intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">suppliers have made an intra-Community supply of VAT-exempt goods to taxable persons who have not been registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In these cases, the supply should not be exempt from VAT and should be subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">Suppliers reported intra-Community supplies in their VAT returns at a higher value than those reported by the purchasers in intra-Community acquisitions, with in some cases VAT being declared incorrectly.</seg>
<seg id="60">The findings of the audit showed that VIES provides tax administrations with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">In particular, tax administrations should pay increased attention to the thorough examination of differences between the data reported by VAT payers and the data in the VIES system and the use of all information in tax proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="62">The issue of value added tax after the accession of the Czech Republic and Slovakia to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1 May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">After joining the EU, internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within the EU were abolished.</seg>
<seg id="66">Until 30 April 2004, the VAT administrator was the relevant financial, resp. the tax office, with the exception of the import of goods and occasional bus transport in the country, where the customs office was the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No. 235/2004 Coll., On value added tax (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 235/2004 Coll.”), Resp. Act No. 222/2004 Coll., on value added tax (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 222/2004 Coll.”), the VAT administration on the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU member states customs offices on the financial, resp. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The delivery of goods in the Czech Republic pursuant to the provisions of Section 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of the goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">A delivery of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is a delivery of goods that have actually been dispatched or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 64 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. it is an exempt taxable supply with the right to deduct VAT if the goods are supplied to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 8 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods owned by a taxable person from the country to another Member State shall also be considered a supply of goods if the goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 43 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., The supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the acquirer is a person identified for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">By acquiring goods from another EU member state, in the Czech Republic, in accordance with the provisions of Section 16 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods which are dispatched or transported to the acquirer by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech taxpayer purchases goods at a price excluding VAT and is obliged to declare VAT in the Czech Republic in accordance with the provisions of Section 25 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll.</seg>
<seg id="76">Acquisition of goods domestically from another EU member state in the Slovak Republic pursuant to the provisions of Section 11 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll. another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">The tax liability in the Slovak Republic arises for the taxpayer when acquiring goods in the country from another Member State pursuant to the provisions of Section 20 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll.</seg>
<seg id="78">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 49 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., The payer may deduct VAT if the tax is applied by him when acquiring goods in the country from another Member State pursuant to the provisions of Sections 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">According to the provisions of Section 17 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., Resp. § 45 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., A trade concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States, where the subject of the trade is the supply of the same goods between these three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intra-Community transactions are defined as supplies and acquisitions of goods between VAT payers in different EU Member States.</seg>
