<seg id="82">VIES system</seg>
<seg id="83">In order to monitor the exercise of the right to VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies of goods, a VAT information exchange system has been set up within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes the electronic VIES system, which allows the tax administrations of the EU Member States to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt the taxable supply from VAT and, conversely, whether the acquirer duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralized within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State is developing its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">The national systems work on a common principle and are interconnected through the EU's common communication network, the so-called CCN (Common Communication Network; see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was connected to the automated tax information system (hereinafter referred to as “ADIS”), in the Slovak Republic to the application software of the tax information system (hereinafter referred to as “APV DIS”).</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems use financial, resp. tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in the administration of taxes and fees.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU member state obtains information about tax entities that it would not be able to obtain on its own without this cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main goal of international administrative cooperation is to combat tax evasion and tax loss.</seg>
<seg id="93">Pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, each Member State designates a central unit within the internal organizational structure in the field of administrative cooperation between EU Member States in the administration of VAT, the so-called CLO (Central Liaison Office).</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, tasks arising from international cooperation are performed by the Ministry of Finance - Central Finance and Tax Directorate, where the Department of International Cooperation in VAT Administration (hereinafter referred to as the “MF CLO”) was established.</seg>
<seg id="95">The function of the CLO in the Slovak Republic is performed by the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic, Department of International Administrative Cooperation (hereinafter referred to as the “DR CLO”).</seg>
<seg id="96">Among other things, these departments communicate with foreign EU administrations, especially in the area of ​​information exchange within the VIES system, exchange of spontaneous information and information at the request of EU tax administrations, coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax audits, verification of tax identification numbers (hereinafter "VAT number") registered for VAT in other EU Member States and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to verify a certain intra-Community transaction or to obtain other information related to a specific tax entity, they send financial, resp. tax authorities through MF CLO, resp. DR CLO to EU requests for information.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these requests, they obtain information from the requested Member States which they can use for the correct assessment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information are usually sent between the CLOs of the EU Member States in electronic form, using a standardized SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="100">Selected audit findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="101">The cooperation between the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was focused primarily on the examination of selected intra-Community transactions carried out between the two states and also on the level of use of information obtained in the form of international financial cooperation, resp. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="102">The SAO, CR requested the SAO SR to examine in 30 cases business transactions carried out between 19 Czech and 25 Slovak tax subjects.</seg>
<seg id="103">The SAO SR requested the SAO, CR to examine in 10 cases business transactions carried out between 7 Slovak and 10 Czech tax subjects.</seg>
<seg id="104">Examination of intra-Community transactions revealed, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="105">O</seg>
<seg id="106">The SAO, CR requested the SAO SR to examine the procedure of the tax administrator, to whom a reply to the request for information was sent.</seg>
<seg id="107">The Slovak Tax Office requested, via the SCAC form, an inspection of the supply of goods (footwear) in the 3rd quarter of 2004 from a Slovak taxpayer in the amount of 2,847,000 CZK. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="108">The Tax Office in the Czech Republic replied that the Czech taxpayer stated the acquisition of goods in this value only in the additional VAT return and delivered the same goods back to Slovak tax subjects in the amount of 2,550,000 CZK by the end of 2004. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="109">Based on the international cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR, it was found that the locally competent tax office recognized the Slovak supplier's full right to an excessive VAT deduction arising, inter alia, from this supply.</seg>
<seg id="110">This tax office did not provide information on suspicion of re-export to the tax authorities of the locally competent customers of goods imported back from the Czech taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="111">These facts will be an incentive for further investigation of business activities in connection with possible carousel fraud.</seg>
<seg id="112">O</seg>
<seg id="113">The Czech tax administrator requested, via the SCAC form, an inspection of the supply of a technological line to the Slovak Republic in the amount of 4,850,000 CZK. CZK in the 2nd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="114">The tax proceedings conducted in the Slovak Republic showed that only a part of the technological line, a component in the amount of 3,395,000 CZK, was delivered. CZK were not delivered.</seg>
<seg id="115">In examining this case, the SAO SR found that the VAT from the taxable supply was declared by the Slovak tax entity from the amount of 4,850,000 CZK. CZK in the tax return for VAT (hereinafter referred to as "DAP") for the tax period 7/2004.</seg>
<seg id="116">The SAO, CR also found that the Czech taxpayer reported an excessive VAT deduction of CZK 655 thousand in the DAP for the said quarter. CZK, which arose from the application of a VAT deduction from the purchase of this technological line from another domestic payer.</seg>
<seg id="117">Based on the results of the investigation, the Czech Tax Office came to the conclusion that the Czech and Slovak tax entities established a business relationship for the purpose of unauthorized acquisition of excessive VAT deduction, questioned the taxable supply and did not recognize the Czech taxpayer part of the tax deduction. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="118">O</seg>
<seg id="119">In 2004, the Slovak tax administrator requested, via the SCAC form, an inspection of the supply of goods (copiers) to a Czech taxpayer in the amount of CZK 24,246 thousand. SKK made in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="120">In November 2002, the Slovak payer purchased these goods in the Slovak Republic from another tax entity in the amount of CZK 29,667 thousand. Sk and subsequently sold it to a Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Slovak tax entity claimed an excessive VAT deduction for the relevant tax period.</seg>
<seg id="122">In a tax investigation conducted in the Czech Republic, it was found that the Czech tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administrator and did not file a DAP for the 4th quarter of 2002 or for the following period.</seg>
<seg id="123">The SAO SR found that the Slovak tax administrator, on the basis of the result of the tax audit, did not recognize the right to an excessive deduction in the amount of CZK 5,541 thousand. SKK applied in the DAP for the month 11/2002 and set the tax liability in the amount of 1,750 thous. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="124">At the same time, this taxable person was not granted an exemption from VAT on exports of goods in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="125">O</seg>
<seg id="126">The Czech tax administrator received an order from the Ministry of Finance CLO to verify the value of the acquired goods for the 3rd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="127">According to VIES data, the Czech payer was to procure goods (diluent) from the Slovak Republic in the amount of 3,767,000 CZK. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="128">This tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administrator, did not file a DAP and VAT for the months 7 to 12/2004 was assessed ex officio in the amount of CZK 0.</seg>
<seg id="129">The Czech tax administrator requested, via the SCAC form, a check on whether the deliveries of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic took place, in what quantity and price (according to invoices).</seg>
<seg id="130">In response, the Slovak locally competent tax office sent a copy of the invoice, bills of lading and a request for payment of the invoice.</seg>
<seg id="131">The SAO SR found that the Slovak taxpayer was granted an exemption with the right to deduct VAT on this supply.</seg>
<seg id="132">The SAO, CR found that the Czech tax administrator evaluated the response to a request for information received from the Slovak Republic as evidence proving that the company acquired goods from another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="133">Based on further investigation, the tax office in the Czech Republic will request a superior body to review the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="134">O</seg>
<seg id="135">The Slovak company supplied goods (chipboard products) to, among others, an American company, which stored these goods in the Czech Republic in a free customs zone.</seg>
<seg id="136">The operator of this free zone was indicated on the invoices as the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="137">In 2004, for example, an American company purchased chipboard tiles in the amount of USD 57,600 (at a unit price of USD 100 / piece) from a Slovak payer, which it placed in a free customs zone.</seg>
<seg id="138">Subsequently, this company transferred ownership of the goods to a Swiss company in the amount of USD 14,400 (unit price USD 25 / piece) and the goods were exported back to the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods were not unloaded in the Czech Republic, but left the free customs zone on the same means of transport.</seg>
<seg id="140">The Slovak tax administrator initiated tax inspections of individual tax periods in 2004 and 2005 at the supplier of goods on suspicion of carousel transactions.</seg>
<seg id="141">Verification of completed transactions was requested from the Czech locally competent tax administrators via several SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="142">The individual answers gradually created a picture of trade and confirmed the involvement of stakeholders from the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in carousel trade.</seg>
<seg id="143">The SAO, the Czech Republic, in cooperation with the SAO SR, found that in these business relations there was a deliberate gradual several-fold reduction in the value of goods.</seg>
<seg id="144">Based on the information obtained, the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic concluded that in this case of carousel trade it is free pricing (ie import of undervalued goods and their overvaluation by domestic companies located in the chain between importer and exporter), which is not an infringement in Slovakia. VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="145">Under current legislation, it is not possible to prevent the payment of excessive VAT deductions to export companies, as they meet all the conditions of the law on the exemption of supplies from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="146">O</seg>
<seg id="147">As of 12 July 2005, the Czech taxpayer's VAT registration was canceled.</seg>
<seg id="148">On 27 October 2005, this entity became a taxpayer again on the basis of a voluntarily submitted application for VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Czech tax entity entered in the DAP for the month of 8/2005 (ie the period when it was not a VAT payer) the value of the acquisition of goods (polygraphic printing machine) from the Slovak Republic in the amount of 1,174 thous. CZK and claimed the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="150">This value corresponded to the delivery of goods from the Slovak payer in the amount of 1,530 thousand. Sk, which the Slovak payer stated in the DAP as a supply of goods to another EU member state with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="151">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify the said supply via the SCAC form, because the Slovak supplier did not prove how he acquired the goods delivered to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO, CR found that the Czech taxpayer does not cooperate with the tax administrator and does not reside at the address specified in the Commercial Register.</seg>
<seg id="153">As part of the international exchange of information, a local investigation will be carried out in the Czech Republic by the locally competent tax administrator in order to verify the data.</seg>
<seg id="154">O</seg>
<seg id="155">The Slovak payer stated in the summary report for the 3rd quarter of 2004 the delivery of goods in the amount of 956 thous. SKK to a tax subject from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">The VAT number of the Czech entity was marked as incorrect by the VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="157">Verification in the database of payers revealed that such a VAT number was never assigned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="158">According to the invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was an electrical installation work on real estate in the Czech Republic, it was not a supply of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="159">The services were invoiced without VAT, as the Czech entity informed the Slovak entity that it was registered in the Czech Republic as a VAT payer.</seg>
<seg id="160">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify the above facts via the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="161">The SAO, Czech Republic, inquired with the locally competent tax administrator in the Czech Republic, found that the tax entity listed on the invoices as a customer was never registered in the Czech Republic as a VAT payer, did not declare tax on services received from a Slovak entity.</seg>
<seg id="162">No local investigation or tax audit was carried out at the Czech entity, its current residence is not known.</seg>
<seg id="163">Based on the international exchange of information, the Czech tax administrator learned that the Czech tax entity had become a VAT payer by law by accepting the service.</seg>
<seg id="164">A tax audit will be carried out at the Slovak tax entity for the 1st to 4th quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="165">O</seg>
<seg id="166">The Slovak payer stated in the summary report for the 3rd quarter of 2004 the delivery of goods in the amount of 1,055 thous. To the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="167">According to the invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was an electrical installation work on real estate in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="168">It was not a delivery of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="169">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify the above facts via the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="170">The SAO, Czech Republic, inquired with the locally competent tax administrator in the Czech Republic, found out that the Czech entity was a VAT payer at the time of delivery and a local investigation was carried out to verify the acquisition of goods from other EU Member States in 2004 Q3.</seg>
<seg id="171">Based on this local investigation, it was found that in the given case it was not really the acquisition of goods, but the acquisition of services, which the Czech entity also reported in the regular DAP.</seg>
<seg id="172">The Tax Office also found that, as a result of a poor procedure in calculating VAT, the Czech entity did not pay the correct amount of VAT for the tax period of the 3rd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="173">The taxable person submits an additional DAP.</seg>
<seg id="174">By asking the locally competent tax office, the SAO SR found out that the Slovak taxpayer had incorrectly stated the provision of the service in the summary report and that a tax audit would be carried out for the 1st to 4th quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="175">O</seg>
