<seg id="349">The acquisition of goods in the DAP was not reported by the tax subject; according to the company's managing director, the goods were transported directly from the Czech Republic to Ukraine in the transit regime.</seg>
<seg id="350">The taxable person did not submit any VAT records during the local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="351">A tax audit was initiated at the payer.</seg>
<seg id="352">5.2 International exchange of L3 level information</seg>
<seg id="353">The exchange of information at the L3 level is initiated by the locally competent tax administrators, who send their requests for information (hereinafter referred to as “FIFG”) or spontaneous information (hereinafter referred to as “SPI”) relating to a specific tax entity or transaction via MF CLO, resp. .</seg>
<seg id="354">DR CLO to another EU member state. The aim of the ŽOI is, for example, to prove the execution of a given transaction within the framework of intra-community services, verification of a certain VAT number, etc.</seg>
<seg id="355">In the case of SPI, this is the communication of information important to tax administrators in another EU member state.</seg>
<seg id="356">Cooperation in the field of information exchange is governed by Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="357">The maximum time limit for replying to the SOI was set in Article 8 of this Regulation at 3 months.</seg>
<seg id="358">The conditions for the admissibility of applications are governed by the Decision of the Commission of the European Communities of 15 November 2004, which stipulates that, unless the participating States agree otherwise, the FDI must cover commercial transactions of at least EUR 1 500 excluding VAT.</seg>
<seg id="359">If the ŽOI concerns a commercial transaction with a value of less than EUR 15 000 excluding VAT, the requested authority may refuse to reply in view of its workload.</seg>
<seg id="360">The procedure of processing incoming ZOIs by the Tax Administration of the Czech Republic, including the indication of internal time limits set for processing at individual organizational levels, is shown in the following diagram.</seg>
<seg id="361">In the Slovak Republic, the deadline for the settlement of ZOI by the tax authorities was set internally at 2 months so that the three-month deadline pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No. 1798/2003 could be met.</seg>
<seg id="362">From 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005, the MF CLO received a total of 29 ŽOI and 3 SPI from the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="363">Of the 29 accepted ŽOI, 26 (ie 89.7%) were settled within the set period of 3 months and 3 (ie 10.3%) were settled after this period.</seg>
<seg id="364">In the same period, the DR CLO from the Czech Republic received a total of 71 ŽOI and 7 SPI.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 accepted ŽOI, 64 (ie 90.1%) were settled within the set period of 3 months, 5 (ie 7.0%) were settled after this period (in the remaining 2 cases it was not possible to determine the settlement period from the submitted materials).</seg>
<seg id="366">More detailed data on the processing time of ŽOI received by MF CLO, resp. DR CLO contains the following graph.</seg>
<seg id="367">The reasons for sending ŽOI, stated on the SCAC forms, are given in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">International cooperation examined compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT and the use of VIES for the exchange of information between EU Member States, in particular in monitoring the exercise of the right to VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to examine selected intra-Community transactions carried out between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="371">Examination of selected transactions revealed that, based on the international exchange of information, the tax administrations of both countries revealed cases of companies making fictitious intra-Community business transactions to obtain excessive VAT deductions, as well as cases where purchasers did not declare VAT correctly.</seg>
<seg id="372">The audit also revealed differences in the processing and use of data from the VIES system by the tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also pointed to problems caused by different reporting of data on intra-Community supplies and acquisitions of goods in different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">Unification of the conditions for reporting these data within the EU would lead to more efficient control activities of the tax administrations of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="375">By checking the financial procedure, resp. tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system, it was found that the financial resp. the tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal authorizations.</seg>
<seg id="376">Furthermore, it was found that the VIES system did not provide up-to-date information on supplies of goods and on the validity of VAT registration of taxable persons in all cases.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared data on the occurrence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the inspection, with data processed after the end of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="378">From the comparison of these data, it was clear that the SAO SR's inspection had an effect not only on reducing the number of SHs with incorrectly stated VAT numbers, but also on reducing the number of uncorrected errors in the SHs.</seg>
<seg id="379">In the event of discrepancies in the reported data, the SAO SR requested the tax authorities to carry out local investigations, or to carry out tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, CR did not have such a possibility within the valid legal regulation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The findings of the audits showed that the VIES system provided tax administrations with the basic information necessary to control the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">Given that there is still room for tax evasion in this area, increased attention needs to be paid to intra-Community transactions in the administration of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communique</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Chairman of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
