<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material provides an overview of the course and results of parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of ​​value added and excise duty administration.</seg>
<seg id="4">The co - operation between the supreme audit institutions of the two countries was carried out on the basis of an agreement on co - operation in control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel audits was chosen in view of the fact that indirect taxes contribute significantly to the revenues of the state budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The construction of value added tax, enabling the refund of the excessive deduction, provides scope for tax fraud, resp. leaks.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duties, especially on tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation by selling these goods illegally.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively throughout the European Union, the VAT Working Group was created by the supreme audit institutions of the member states of the European Union, in the activities of which the supreme audit institutions of both countries are also actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the inspections carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but especially in the joint effort to identify problem areas in the administration of indirect taxes in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience and knowledge gained will be used in the planned controls of indirect taxes, focused primarily on the involvement of tax administrations of both countries in the VIES system, which allows to control the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties for the period of 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Inspection number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the procedure of the tax administrator in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2. In 2004, an Agreement on Cooperation in Audit Activities was concluded between the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO") and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO SR"). The subject of the agreement was cooperation in parallel inspections "Value Added Tax and Excise Duties", included in the SAO's plan of control activities for 2004 under No. 04/07 and "Control of the procedure of the tax administrator in the administration, control and recovery of value added tax". and excise duties ", included in the plan of control activities of the SAO SR under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent specified in the concluded contract and in the preparation of a joint final report on the result of inspections.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, both parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, the customs administration database and the files of tax entities kept by tax authorities in the Czech Republic and tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the parties could not obtain taxes on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the State concerned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The inspections were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "Czech Republic"), the inspection was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of South Bohemia, North-East Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The auditees were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected tax offices: the Tax Office for Prague 1, the Tax Office for Prague 3, the Tax Office in České Budějovice, the Tax Office in Frýdek-Místek, the Tax Office in Hodonín, the Tax Office in Jihlava, the Tax Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, Financial Office in Kroměříž, Financial Office in Písek, Financial Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, Financial Office in Velké Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The inspection on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SR”) was carried out by the Tax and Customs Administration Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice Branches at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax Office Bratislava for selected tax subjects, Tax Office Bratislava III, Tax Office Trnava, Tax Office Pú-chov, Tax Office Banská Bystrica I, Tax Office Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax Office Žilina I, Tax Office Žilina II, Tax Office Košice I and Tax Office Košice Office IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the inspections was to verify the fulfillment of financial obligations, resp. tax offices and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise duties with a focus on the collection of these taxes in the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns on the relevant financial, resp. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited periods were 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">As part of international cooperation, the SAO handed over 22,206 items of single customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as "SAD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and the SAO SR handed over 30,221 SAD items from the Slovak customs database.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison of selected SAD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic was performed.</seg>
<seg id="34">Out of 5,883 selected SAD items from the Czech customs database, a total of 43% of related SAD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Out of 12,343 selected SAD items from the customs database of the Slovak Republic, a total of 26% of related SAD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">Based on unallocated items, the SAD was on the financial, respectively. The tax authorities selected the files of tax entities for which the reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">On the basis of the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and financial, resp. In the territory of the other state, the realization of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic performed a joint pilot inspection at the Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma border customs crossing, during which both parties cooperated closely in verifying the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="39">The inspection did not reveal any deficiencies in the records of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation enabled the examination of trade transactions carried out between trading partners from both countries and pointed to shortcomings in the records of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of inspection results</seg>
<seg id="42">The audit of the SAO and the SAO SR in the area of ​​international cooperation focused on imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, or other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">Based on the control of files of tax subjects on selected financial, resp. The SAO asked the SAOs to verify the implementation of exports of goods reported at 40 SADs in the total statistical value of CZK 15,301,093 and the SAO of the Slovak Republic to verify the exports in the statistical value of SKK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO SR found out, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="46">- the error rate in entering data into the customs databases made it impossible to identify some imports, resp. exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- for some exports from the Czech Republic, corresponding imports to the Slovak Republic were not proven.</seg>
<seg id="48">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of unduly applying VAT deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- the taxable persons did not comply with certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- in financial activities, resp. shortcomings were identified in the administration of value added tax and excise duties and in their cooperation with customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of ​​value added tax and excise duties, attention will continue to be paid to international trade in order to effectively minimize tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">It is especially important to improve the activities of tax administrators in the performance of value added tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis of effective control of excise duties is the control of the circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information during the import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the situation in the field of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") was levied by the tax or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out in the country and by the customs authorities on the import of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">Tax revenues were for financial, resp. tax authorities due to the difference between the collected own tax liability and the refunded excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenues at customs offices were given by the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">In accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, the tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected in the tax deductions applied to the financial, resp. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most financial, resp. excessive deductions of VAT exceeded the tax liability of tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="61">In terms of state budget revenues, VAT is one of the key taxes, as it accounted for approximately 31% of the Czech state budget revenues in 2003 and approximately 42% of the Slovak state budget revenues.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic in 2003 amounted to CZK 162.9 billion.</seg>
<seg id="63">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT and the refunded excess VAT deductions totaled CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total VAT collection in the Slovak Republic in 2003 amounted to SKK 83.8 billion.</seg>
<seg id="65">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected SKK 187.0 billion for VAT, and the refunded excess VAT deductions totaled SKK 103.2 billion.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "SpD") was carried out by the relevant financial, resp. tax authorities and, in the case of imports of products subject to SPD, customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of SpD in the tax revenues of the state budget in the Czech Republic in 2003 was approximately 16% and in the Slovak Republic approximately 19%.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SpD collected in the Czech Republic by financial and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to CZK 85.6 billion and in the Slovak Republic reached SKK 38.0 billion.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. The course of the control action</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was performed;</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel inspections of VAT and SpD was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO SR in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">A coordination meeting took place in November 2003, at which, among other things, the selection of commodities was agreed - types of goods that posed a significant risk of compliance with customs and tax regulations: - alcohol and spirits, tariff items 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products , tariff headings Nos. 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff headings and subheadings Nos 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile telephones and their accessories, tariff subheadings 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax subjects for control will be made: a) from unallocated items determined by comparing exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, b) from entities carrying out imports and exports regularly or once in large volumes, c) based on findings from inspections carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases in the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, the mechanism of mutual allocation of SAD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was tested on a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities in October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, a part of exports from the Czech Republic was compared with imports to the Slovak Republic in 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol or higher; ethyl alcohol and other spirits, denatured, of any strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unmanufactured tobacco; tobacco waste,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars, cheroots, cigarillos and cigarettes, of tobacco or of tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other manufactured tobacco and manufactured tobacco substitutes; homogenized or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and essences (essences),</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmitting apparatus incorporating receiving equipment: For the cellular network (mobile telephones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmitting apparatus incorporating receiving equipment: Other,</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with the apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling within subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">SAD items from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were assigned to each other on the basis of compliance of individual SAD paragraphs (eg invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration number of the vehicle transporting cargo, date of crossing the state border, tariff item, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are shown in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">The mutual allocation of individual imports and exports was hampered, among other things, by the fact that trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic declared on one export SAD were declared on several import SADs in the territory of the Slovak Republic, or the export SAD had a different number of items from the import SAD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that influenced the success of the assignment were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, as well as the time shift between the records of exports in the customs database of one country and the records of corresponding imports in the customs database of another country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples for the audited financial, resp. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that carried out imports, resp. exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">Furthermore, for the verification of business transactions reported in VAT tax returns, some tax entities were selected for which data on imports, resp. exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot control at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border customs crossing</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing for the performance of pilot control was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unallocated SAD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="100">Based on a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, the use of checklists was introduced at the border customs crossings between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic on 1 June 1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as much as possible, to ensure an overview of the movement of means of transport transporting goods of a commercial nature in the customs area and to create conditions for mutual comparison of customs records.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot inspection took place from 8 March 2004 to 26 March 2004 and was aimed at verifying this system of customs control.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for using checklists at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border customs crossing:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Weighing the vehicle, issuing a checklist and handing it over to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Parking the vehicle in the marked sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs hearing in the check-in hall of the Police of the Czech Republic, the Police of the Slovak Republic, the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The individual check-in was confirmed by the individual components by imprinting a stamp on the checklist.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Delivery of the vehicle to the physical inspection area.</seg>
<seg id="109">Submission of a control sheet, SAD, or other documents to a customs administration employee - control of the performance of all prescribed acts and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Perform a physical inspection by the appropriate components.</seg>
<seg id="111">Release of the vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">Note: When importing goods into the Czech Republic, the weighing of the vehicle was performed directly by employees of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When importing goods into the Slovak Republic, the weighing of the vehicle was performed by employees of an authorized legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were recorded in the computer records after consideration.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of exports of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the control sample for exports is given in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Checklists and their records Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="120">When exporting from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these checklists in the electronic export database.</seg>
<seg id="122">From the number of 453 SAD items, the SAO SR traced 256 cases of imports into the SR according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic. The remaining 197 items of the SAD were identified by the SAO SR in cooperation with the staff of the Drietoma border customs crossing.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exporting from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">Out of the total number of 339 SAD items of the selected control sample, the SAO, in cooperation with the staff of the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov, assigned the corresponding registration numbers of control sheets to 295 SAD items.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases were identified in their records by Drietoma border customs officers and confirmed the export of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="127">The audit of the SAO and the SAO SR did not find deficiencies in the records of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border customs crossing.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected audit findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified from the documents of customs administrations and financial, resp. tax authorities in the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="130">The following was verified for selected tax subjects:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted SADs were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfillment of the legal conditions for the application of the VAT deduction on importation, refund of the excessive VAT deduction and application of the VAT exemption on exportation.</seg>
<seg id="133">Verification of business transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO SR requested verification of the implementation of alcohol exports in the statistical value of SKK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified in the customs database of the Czech Republic the corresponding imports in the statistical value of CZK 42,624</seg>
<seg id="136">2. A company engaged in the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories claimed an excessive VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in its VAT return for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to control reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO collected 3 SADs (16 items) with a statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO SR identified 3 corresponding import SADs (17 items) with a statistical value of SKK 1,724,321.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid in the Slovak Republic to the relevant customs office.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. In 2002, a company whose object of business was mainly the trade in optical instruments claimed a total excess VAT deduction of CZK 4,136,000 higher than the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="141">To verify the reported business activity, the SAO selected an export SAD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO SR found that this SAD corresponds to the import SAD (12 items) with a statistical value of SKK 9,653,827.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid in the Slovak Republic to the relevant customs office.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company dealing, inter alia, with the purchase of goods for resale and resale, did not report any exports of goods in the VAT and tax returns submitted in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the Czech customs database, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 totaled CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected 5 export SADs (5 items) for verification with a total statistical value of CZK 669,839.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO SR identified 5 corresponding import SADs (5 items) in the statistical value of SKK 1,012,656.</seg>
<seg id="148">The SAO SR's inspection at the relevant tax office proved that the declared imports and the payment of VAT had taken place.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company, whose object of business was, inter alia, the purchase of goods for resale and the sale, manufacture, installation and repair of electrical machinery and apparatus, reported in 2002 in VAT tax returns the export of goods in the amount of CZK 12,966,706.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the Czech customs database, the total value of exports in 2002 was CZK 14,474,381.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export SADs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR identified 13 SADs (50 items) in the customs database of the SR in the statistical value of SKK 3,621,370.</seg>
<seg id="153">The customs database of the Slovak Republic failed to identify the corresponding import SAD for 4 export SADs (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 399,776.</seg>
<seg id="154">The relevant tax office in the Slovak Republic verified these imports with the tax subject.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity listed on the SAD as an importer in the Slovak Republic stated in the minutes of the local investigation that it did not realize the imports declared on the Czech export SADs.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO SR therefore asked the local competent tax office to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate income tax for the 2002 and 2003 tax periods.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, a company engaged in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco labels in 2002 with a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 and in 2003 with a statistical value of CZK 12,228,545.</seg>
<seg id="158">In 2002 and 2003, the company did not report any exports in its VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected 5 export SADs (5 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598 for verification.</seg>
<seg id="160">For 4 export SADs (4 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,246,860, the SAO SR identified 7 SADs (7 items) with a statistical value of SKK 2,919,514 in the customs database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="161">In the customs database of the Slovak Republic, it was not possible to assign the corresponding import to the export SAD (1 item) in the statistical value of CZK 224,738.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software company did not report exports of goods in the 2002 and 2003 VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the Czech customs database, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 and 2003 totaled CZK 1,630,198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 SADs (9 items) for verification in the SR in the total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic, the SAO SR identified 8 SADs (8 items) with a statistical value of SKK 915,601.</seg>
<seg id="166">Corresponding imports could not be assigned to the export SAD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 68,286 in the customs database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="167">In the above cases, it was not possible to identify in the customs database of the Slovak Republic the corresponding imports to 6 SADs in the statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- for 2 export SADs from the customs database of the Czech Republic in the statistical value of CZK 293,024, it was not possible to identify the corresponding import SADs in the customs database of the Slovak Republic (see points 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error in entering data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify some registered imports, eg in cases where the importer's name was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (hereinafter "VAT number").</seg>
<seg id="171">Therefore, it cannot be stated with certainty that these exports did not take place.</seg>
<seg id="172">- for 4 export SADs from the customs database of the Czech Republic, imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic in the statistical value of CZK 399,776 were not proven (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious export of goods for the purpose of unauthorized application of the VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services within the control of selected financial, resp. tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfillment of the obligations of tax subjects in the import and export of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the financial and customs authorities, the audited financial, resp. files of tax subjects are selected by the tax authorities according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax subjects were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic: a) with the highest volume of imports, b) with the highest amount of assessed VAT, c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. from the records of financial, resp. tax authorities were selected by the tax authorities according to the above: a) applied VAT deductions on import, b) applied excessive VAT deductions, c) the right to a refund of the SPD, d) applied exemption from VAT on export,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities for which a tax audit has been performed.</seg>
<seg id="180">The selection of the sample was made regardless of the country of destination, focusing on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Control findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Inspection of a selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="184">At the audited financial authorities, the SAO focused mainly on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure of the tax authorities in verifying the correctness of the VAT declared,</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between tax authorities and the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparison of data from the customs database with the SAD database at tax offices with a focus on the comparison of the declared value, application of the correct VAT rate in connection with the customs classification of goods or services, or comparison of data on the SAD and attached invoices with data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- comparison of data from VAT tax returns on completed and received transactions from abroad with data in the SAD database at tax offices or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- the method of verifying entitlement to the VAT exemption for the export of goods or the provision of services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services provided reported in VAT returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The SAD database at tax offices only contained records on those imports and exports for which tax subjects were obliged to state imports or exports in the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The files of tax subjects were examined at the audited tax offices, which reported in the tax returns for VAT in 2002 and 2003 imports in the total amount of 60,396,379 thousand CZK. CZK and the corresponding VAT in the total amount of 12,644,052 thous. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="193">Furthermore, the files of tax subjects reporting exports in the tax returns for the years 2002 and 2003 in the total value of 47,323,111 thousand CZK were checked. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, tax entities in which imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were inspected in 2002 and 2003 carried out imports into the Czech Republic from the Slovak Republic with a total VAT base of 3,759,352 thousand CZK. CZK, VAT in the amount of 767 607 thous. CZK and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of 1,989,090 thous. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="195">The detected differences between the records in the SAD database at the tax authorities and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- SAD items that were missing in the Czech customs database were requested directly from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- for SAD items that were missing from the tax office database, it was verified that they were not canceled documents,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for SAD items for which different values ​​were found between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of tax authorities, the relevant SAD was requested at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in writing, including the attached invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">During the examination, it was found that the SAD database at tax offices did not contain, for example, records on import SADs in the total value of VAT of 3,622 thousand CZK. CZK and records on export SADs in the total statistical value of 9,359 thous. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Identified differences</seg>
<seg id="201">A comparison of the SAD database at tax offices and the cumulative tax obligations for 2002 and 2003 in VAT returns for a selected sample of tax entities revealed the following differences:</seg>
<seg id="202">The differences in values ​​were mainly caused by:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time lag between the realization of imports and the exercise of the right to deduct VAT assessed on the import of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The tax subject could claim the right to deduct tax on the import of goods within 3 years from the end of the tax period in which the goods were released into the relevant regime, respectively. in the case of a temporary importation scheme, no later than 3 years from the end of the tax period in which the scheme was terminated.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time lag between the realization of the export and the moment when the tax subject received the SAD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The taxable person was obliged to state data on realized exports exempted from the obligation to apply output tax in the VAT return at the earliest for the tax period in which the goods left the country, if he also had a tax document, which was the SAD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure of taxpayers to fulfill their obligations when reporting imports and exports in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, taxable persons did not provide correct data on imports and exports in their VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">Due to the fact that tax subjects did not have to attach SAD lists to the submitted VAT tax returns, it was difficult for the tax authorities to control the right to deduct VAT or exemption from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Cooperation between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the period under review, import or export duties and VAT were repaid or remitted on the basis of a decision of the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax entities were obliged by law to reduce the previously claimed right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax refunded by the customs office, in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation regulated the sending of information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT from customs offices to tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax offices received this information, but irregularly or with a significant time lag, and only from some customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax office did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the data needed to check compliance with the legal obligation of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, the customs authorities refunded VAT in the amount of more than CZK 319 million and in 2003 in the amount of over CZK 398 million.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit pointed to persistent shortcomings in the activities of tax administrators, some systemic errors in the cooperation of tax authorities with customs authorities and non-compliance with certain obligations of taxpayers filing tax returns for VAT and SpD.</seg>
<seg id="219">Weaknesses were identified in the administration of VAT and SpD, especially in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">a) upon cancellation of VAT registrations, the fulfillment of the payers' obligation to pay VAT on commercial property registered or which should have been registered on the day of cancellation of the registration, for which the payer claimed tax deduction, was verified only sporadically,</seg>
<seg id="221">(b) the tax authorities have not consistently exercised the possibility to carry out a tax audit or a local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="222">In some cases, this led to insufficient verification of the legitimacy of the right to deduct VAT,</seg>
<seg id="223">c) the official records and minutes of the oral proceedings did not contain all the necessary information to substantiate the excessive VAT deductions applied,</seg>
<seg id="224">(d) the tax authorities did not sufficiently verify the imports and exports reported in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in the SR</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Inspection of a selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For a selected sample, the SAO SR verified or the tax office performed a tax audit for the tax periods of 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analyzing the submitted tax returns and applications for tax refunds at selected tax entities, the SAO SR requested the tax office to provide the relevant SADs documenting imports and exports, invoices and documents for tax payment.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO SR checked whether the submitted SADs are registered in the customs database of imports and exports and fulfillment of decisive facts and legal conditions when applying the input tax deduction for import, when refunding excessive VAT deduction, when applying exemption from export tax and when refunding SpD.</seg>
<seg id="230">The SAO SR verified selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the SR and the CR at 10 audited tax offices in the structure according to the number of SAD items and the sum of statistical values ​​given in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports in the statistical value of SKK 856.2 million were checked, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic to the SRO.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked in the total statistical value of SKK 176 million, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">Furthermore, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white goods, packaging technology and software) from EU countries to the Slovak Republic were inspected in the total statistical value of SKK 532.8 million.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Cooperation between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">During its inspection at the tax authorities, the SAO SR found discrepancies between the data registered in the customs database of the Slovak Republic and the data reported in specific VAT tax returns, eg:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax subjects (natural persons) stated in tax returns imports of goods in the total value of SKK 1,589,261, on the basis of which they claimed the right to a refund of excessive VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">During local investigations carried out at the initiative of the SAO SR, the tax subjects were unable to prove to the tax office the legitimacy of the application of input tax with the relevant documents on the implementation of imports and payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- the tax subject (s. r. o.) declared in the tax return for the tax period January 2003 the received taxable performance in the amount of SKK 77,167,576, the export of goods in the amount of SKK 18,006,041 and claimed an excessive VAT deduction in the amount of SKK 17,157,101.</seg>
<seg id="239">The VAT tax returns filed for 2003 show that the difference between the volume of purchases and exports in the amount of SKK 59,161,535, which arose in January 2003, was not settled throughout 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above-mentioned cases, the SAO SR requested the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the applied excessive VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, a tax entity (s. r. o.) for the tax period January to June 2002 stated in VAT tax returns the export of goods in the total value of SKK 87,199.</seg>
<seg id="242">Verification in the customs database of the Slovak Republic revealed that the tax entity carried out exports in the mentioned period in the statistical value of SKK 296,747.</seg>
<seg id="243">The tax office conducted several local inquiries at the company 's headquarters, finding that the company' s managing director (a UK citizen) had traveled and the company had left the leased premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the SAO SR's inspection, the tax administrator submitted a notification to the authorities involved in criminal proceedings on suspicion of committing a criminal offense of non-payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="245">Based on the results of inspections at selected tax offices, the SAO SR states that the biggest problems in the performance of administration and control of VAT and SpD occurred mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- non-use of the possibility to carry out VAT tax audits of problematic tax subjects, especially in cases of application of a high value of excessive VAT deductions,</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax audit reports did not contain a list of audited documents</seg>
<seg id="248">- SAD for imports and exports of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient verification of reported imports and exports of goods in tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy proceedings of tax administrations in issuing decisions, especially in the context of assessment proceedings, also with the consequence of the expiry of the right to impose sanctions,</seg>
<seg id="251">- non-compliance with legal conditions in the provision of tax deferrals,</seg>
<seg id="252">- non-compensation of VAT arrears within the period for refunding the excess VAT deduction,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and enforcement of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">Based on the inspection of the identified deficiencies, the SAO SR requested the relevant tax authorities to perform a VAT tax audit focusing on the justification of the applied excessive VAT deductions for 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">Measures were taken at all audited tax offices to eliminate the deficiencies identified during the inspection, the fulfillment of which will be monitored and controlled by the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation enabled the examination of trade transactions carried out between trading partners from both countries and pointed to shortcomings in the records of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The result of the inspections was also the finding of persistent deficiencies in the fulfillment of obligations of VAT and SpD payers, in financial activities, resp. tax authorities, in a system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs administrations, which ultimately reduced the efficiency and effectiveness of tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="259">The findings also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have at their disposal basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic within the tax information system. In the Slovak Republic, there is no similar system for transmitting information on imports and exports of goods between the customs and tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the VAT and SpD administration was not the same due to different legal regulations and conditions in the territory of both states.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained from the customs administration of the Czech Republic and from documents available at the audited financial offices. The SAO SR verified the execution of business transactions from the documents of tax subjects requested through the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="263">The parallel inspections carried out in the area of ​​VAT and SPD assessed the state of administration of these taxes in the period before accession to the European Union and pointed to the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further deepened in the control of financial activities, resp. tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT law.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a so-called summary report.</seg>
<seg id="266">This declaration must be submitted by all VAT payers who have made a supply of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrators are obliged to enter data from summary reports into the VIES (VAT Information Exchange System) system, to which tax administrators from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">Financial, resp. the tax authorities then have the opportunity to compare these data with the data stated in the submitted VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is also used to verify the validity of the VAT number of persons registered for VAT, to verify the legitimacy of the applied VAT exemption when delivering goods to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel audits showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these inspections will be confronted with the outputs of the planned inspections, which will, among other things, focus on examining the VIES system, which is intended to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intra-Community supplies".</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SPD for budget revenues, control activities need to focus primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion on indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communique</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice President of the Supreme Audit Office and the Chairman of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
