<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of inspections in asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State property and financial resources intended to ensure the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Inspection Action No. 04/23 "State property and financial resources intended for securing the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Inspection Action No. 15/2004 "Control of the management of state property and funds intended for the provision of asylum and temporary refuge to foreigners in the Slovak Republic"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the phenomena that have a global character and have become an integral part of the current development stages of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">It is mainly due to the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last permanent residence from persecution, in particular for racial, religious, national, political, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their goal is to obtain asylum and integration into society, especially in some of the developed democratic countries in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group also includes foreigners whose reason for migration is unfavorable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The establishment of specific principles for aid to refugees has already led to the adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the Status of Refugees, which the governments of the signatory countries have undertaken to apply in their foreign policy orientations.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federal Republic ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the split in 1993, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to comply with the adopted international documents and confirmed their binding nature within the framework of national legislation by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have enshrined the provision of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic focused on the asylum process and related issues, the results of which are contained in the joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">The co - operation between the supreme audit institutions of the two countries was carried out on the basis of the "Agreement on Co - operation in Control Activities" (hereinafter referred to as the "Agreement") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the Treaty, both parties undertook to provide each other with information on the legislation governing asylum procedures in the other Contracting Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to identify the same problem areas and to point out the consequences that follow from this for the area of ​​population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">The co-operation consisted in the unification of the program of control actions, in the exchange of information to the extent stipulated by the Treaty and in the preparation of a joint final report on the result of controls.</seg>
<seg id="20">At the first joint meeting, which took place on 5.4. to 7.4.2004, identical areas of audited issues and control procedures in the preparation of audits were determined.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place on 28.6. to 30.6. 2004, common points for the control program were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">At the third joint meeting, which took place during the inspection on 8.11. to 10.11.2004, there was an exchange of experience from ongoing inspections.</seg>
<seg id="23">The forms of outputs from inspections were specified and the structure and content of the joint final report, which was prepared on 14.2. to 17.2. 2005 at the last joint meeting.</seg>
<seg id="24">The inspections were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by inspectors of the Department of Defense and Security and selected territorial departments.</seg>
<seg id="26">The inspected persons were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as the "MoI") and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as the "SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic, the inspection was carried out by the Defense, Interior and State Offices Section.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migration Office of the Ministry of the Interior of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "MA").</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2001, 2002, 2003 (hereinafter the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistics for a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of the parallel inspections was: - asylum process, - asylum facilities, - management of financial resources and state property, - internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of experience gained between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic took place in the phase of preparation and implementation of audits.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange made it possible to more thoroughly evaluate the submitted documents, to analyze the causes of the identified differences in the provision of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">Thus, it was possible to focus on the crucial problems affecting the operation of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">Ultimately, this had a positive effect on the quality of control activities.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of inspection results</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonization of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with the documents of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the "EU") was the subject of evaluation reports of the European Commission on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">The adoption of legislation in this area continues after the accession of both countries to the EU with the aim of further harmonization with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has a constantly growing trend, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security to asylum seekers in accordance with international agreements.</seg>
<seg id="44">The state budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditures drawn from the state budget of both countries is influenced mainly by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the granting or non-granting of asylum, and also the health status of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some selected benefits is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic set up asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of participants in asylum proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="48">During the stay of asylum facilities, asylum seekers are provided with accommodation, meals, health care and basic material equipment and hygiene needs.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, courses are organized as part of leisure activities and conditions are created for applicants for cultural and sports activities.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centers and residence centers, and in the Czech Republic also integration centers.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost per day depends on the occupancy and facilities of the center and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is basically stabilized.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is expected to increase by almost 1,000 jobs in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, the growing number of which is expected to continue in the coming years in connection with the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest part of approved budget expenditures was spent on the provision of services. The decisive expenditures of this item were expenditures on accommodation and meals for applicants in asylum facilities operated on the basis of a contract, expenditures on health care provided to asylum seekers and costs for a permanent security service ensuring the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditures on salaries, payments for work performed and insurance premiums also contributed significantly to total expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the migration policy and asylum process was marked by many budgetary measures that addressed the legitimate demands related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditures on wages, salaries and insurance premiums, expenditures on materials and services and expenditures on security services contributed decisively to the use of current expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the inspection in the Czech Republic and in the Slovak Republic pointed out some similar shortcomings which did not have a significant impact on the financial management and management of state property.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were shortcomings, especially in the area of ​​using state budget funds, contrary to the purpose for which they were intended by the State Budget Act, when actions having the character of technical improvement of tangible fixed assets were covered from current expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="61">The law on accounting in the area of ​​inventory and non-compliance with the chart of accounts was also violated.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the management of state property when it was left for use to another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes in the data of the Real Estate Cadastre violated the Real Estate Cadastre Act, and by leaving waste to be disposed of to a person who was not a person authorized to dispose of waste, the Waste Act was violated.</seg>
<seg id="64">In the Slovak Republic, shortcomings were also found in the provision of disproportionately high advances for electricity and natural gas consumption, shortcomings in the award of public contracts and in the management of state property, when its registration was not sufficiently ensured and the method of disposal of unnecessary assets was not proven.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system was ensured in the Czech Republic and in the Slovak Republic in the sense of valid generally binding legal regulations that regulate the method of performing financial control.</seg>
<seg id="66">No deficiencies were found in the submitted written documentation.</seg>
<seg id="67">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, despite some shortcomings identified, evaluate positively the approach of SUZ and MÚ in providing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the findings of the audit, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic state that despite the significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the relevant organizational units of both countries have .</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the inspection were discussed with the interested statutory representatives of the relevant organizational units of the state on the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the audit, we recommend that the positive methodological experience from the audit be used in other joint control events within the framework of international cooperation of supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, the right of asylum is based on the Geneva Convention of 1951 (Convention relating to the Status of Refugees and the related New York Protocol of 1967).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legal regulation was implemented by Act No. 498/1990 Coll., On Refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">In the Czech Republic, Act No. 325/1999 Coll., On Asylum and on the Amendment of Act No. 83/1991 Coll., On the Police of the Czech Republic, has been in force since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act has been amended a total of five times (Act No. 2/2002 Coll., Act No. 217/2002 Coll., Act No. 320/2002 Coll., Act No. 519/2002 Coll. And Act No. 222/2003 Coll. .).</seg>
<seg id="77">Two other amendments to Act No. 325/1999 Coll., On Asylum, are currently in the legislative process, and the adoption of further amendments will be linked to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of drafting Act No. 325/1999 Coll., On asylum, the area of ​​asylum was part of the 3rd pillar of the EU and asylum documents were political documents in terms of binding force.</seg>
<seg id="79">Already in the adoption of this law, there was an effort to make it as compatible as possible with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="80">A significant change for asylum policy within the EU was the transfer of asylum issues from the 3rd to the 1st pillar, when the right of asylum became a part of Community law from 1.5. 1999 on the basis of the Amsterdam Treaty.</seg>
<seg id="81">This shift has created the need to create appropriate legislation, ie. create legal instruments in appropriate legal force.</seg>
<seg id="82">The compatibility of Czech asylum law with EU documents has been the subject of regular evaluation reports by the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="83">Key Community regulations in the field of asylum were adopted shortly before or only after the accession of the Czech Republic to the EU, and their transposition deadline at the time of the Supreme Audit Office's inspection had not yet expired.</seg>
<seg id="84">After their implementation into the Czech legal order, the Czech Republic will be obliged to notify the European Commission of the manner in which it has transposed it.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Slovak Republic, the procedure of state authorities in proceedings on granting refugee status and determining the obligations of foreigners who have applied for refugee status or who have been granted temporary refuge in the Slovak Republic was established with effect from 1 January 1996 by Act No. 283 of the National Council of the Slovak Republic. / 1995 Coll., On refugees.</seg>
<seg id="86">Since 2003, the Act on Refugees has been replaced by Act No. 480/2002 Coll., “On Asylum and on Amendments to Certain Acts, which incorporated the harmonization of the legislation of the Slovak Republic with the Council of Europe Directive 2001/55 / ​​EC of 20 July On minimum standards for providing temporary protection in the event of a mass influx of displaced persons and on measures to promote a balance of efforts between Member States in receiving such persons and bearing the consequences thereof.</seg>
<seg id="87">After two amendments to Act No. 480/2002 Coll., On Asylum, in 2003 and 2004, a third amendment was approved at the beginning of 2005, which means further harmonization of the law of the Slovak Republic with EU legislation in the area of ​​migration and asylum.</seg>
<seg id="88">Its important elements are, for example, the determination of the obligation for asylum seekers to attend a basic Slovak language course during their stay in the integration center, the appointment of a guardian by courts for minors who remain in the Slovak Republic without a legal representative, enabling applicants to enter into employment in the amendment to the law.</seg>
<seg id="89">The harmonization of the law of the Slovak Republic with the EU law in the area of ​​migration and the asylum process was assessed in the regular reports of the European Commission on the readiness of the Slovak Republic to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="90">In 2002, the report drew attention to the insufficient staff capacity of the Municipal Authority, which did not correspond to the increased number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="91">4. Asylum process</seg>
<seg id="92">In the Czech Republic, since 1990, matters concerning refugees have been the responsibility of the Ministry of the Interior.</seg>
<seg id="93">With effect from 1 January 1996, the Ministry of the Interior set up an organizational unit of the SUZ state. The reason was the separation of the performance of state administration in the area of ​​the asylum procedure, which is performed through the Department of Asylum and Migration Policy of the Ministry of the Interior, from the provision of services to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="94">The task of SUZ is to provide the Ministry of the Interior with the provision of accommodation, catering, health and other services to participants in asylum proceedings and asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Slovak Republic, the Municipal Authority performs decisive tasks in the area of ​​the asylum process, especially in terms of financial and material and technical support of the asylum process to the extent defined by special regulations.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority tasks are issues related to deciding on the applications of foreigners for asylum in the first instance of administrative proceedings and the comprehensive operation of asylum facilities in the area of ​​accommodation, catering, health, financial and material security of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, it prepares concepts for the migration policy of the state.</seg>
<seg id="98">The results achieved in the field of creating an asylum system in the Slovak Republic in recent years have been significantly influenced by cooperation and support from the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (hereinafter "UNHCR").</seg>
<seg id="99">A special benefit was his financial participation in the reconstruction of the housing stock for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="100">UNHCR also co-financed social, cultural and sporting activities for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="101">4.1 Development of the number of asylum seekers and results of the asylum process</seg>
<seg id="102">The development of the number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic is shown in the graph.</seg>
<seg id="103">There was a significant increase in 2001 due to the Kosovo crisis, and in 2003 there was an increase in the number of refugees from Chechnya.</seg>
<seg id="104">An overview of the results of the asylum procedure in the Czech Republic is given in Table 1.</seg>
<seg id="105">During the audited period, a total of 394 cases were granted asylum, of which 83 in 2001, 103 in 2002 and 208 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="106">During the audited period, asylum was not granted in a total of 22,731 cases and in 22,636 cases the asylum procedure was terminated.</seg>
<seg id="107">Number of participants in the proceedings as of 1.1. it includes both persons to whom a decision has not yet been issued and those to whom the decision has not been transmitted.</seg>
<seg id="108">Also included are persons who have been forgiven for missing the deadline for filing an appeal, or for whom the previous decision has been annulled and a new one has not yet been issued.</seg>
<seg id="109">In the Slovak Republic, the number of asylum seekers is constantly growing.</seg>
<seg id="110">If in 1993 96 applicants were registered, in 2003 it was already 10,358 persons.</seg>
<seg id="111">There was a significant increase in the number of applicants in 2001, when 8,131 applicants were registered, which represented an increase of 423% compared to 2000, in which 1,556 persons applied for asylum.</seg>
