<seg id="113">In the audited period, a total of 49 asylums were granted and their number did not exceed 0.22% of the registered number of applicants in individual years.</seg>
<seg id="114">Asylum was not granted in 860 cases.</seg>
<seg id="115">Asylum proceedings were discontinued in a total of 23,088 cases.</seg>
<seg id="116">The majority of applicants, by staying without a permit, stayed outside the asylum facility voluntarily left the asylum procedure before its termination.</seg>
<seg id="117">In 2002 it was more than 82% of the total number of registered applicants and in 2003 it was more than 94% of persons.</seg>
<seg id="118">The length of stay of one applicant in one of the asylum facilities, converted to the average number of days, was 13 days in 2001, 18 days in 2002 and 19 days in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="119">The findings of the Ministry of Interior also show that the majority of applicants entering the asylum process in the Slovak Republic are looking for better living conditions, ie so-called economic migration, which has no support in documents adopted by the international community, to which the Slovak Republic has signed up.</seg>
<seg id="120">In these cases, the asylum system is purposefully used by the applicant.</seg>
<seg id="121">An asylum application based on economic reasons, such as seeking employment or better living conditions, is not a ground for granting asylum.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such a request should be in accordance with the provisions of § 12 par. 1 letter a) of Act No. 480/2002 Coll., on Asylum, assessed as manifestly unfounded and should be decided on within 30 days.</seg>
<seg id="123">Internationally recognized principles for identifying economic migrants have not yet been established to distinguish them from applicants persecuted in their country of origin and to speed up the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="124">Given the above facts, it can be stated that the Slovak Republic is a transit country in terms of international migration and the destination countries for migration were and still are Western European countries.</seg>
<seg id="125">Following accession to the EU, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic acceded to the Agreement designating the State responsible for examining applications for asylum lodged in one of the Member States of the European Communities (Dublin Convention).</seg>
<seg id="126">The Convention prevents the submission of multiple targeted asylum applications in several EU countries.</seg>
<seg id="127">Applicants shall return to the country of first registration after a positive identification in EURODAC.</seg>
<seg id="128">The Slovak Republic is part of the external borders of EU countries, therefore the application of the Dublin Convention may result in an increase in the number of applicants who will need to create conditions for residence in the Slovak Republic until a decision on granting or not granting asylum is issued.</seg>
<seg id="129">4.2 Drawing funds</seg>
<seg id="130">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic are obliged to provide financial and material security to asylum seekers in accordance with international agreements and national legislation based on them.</seg>
<seg id="131">The state budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="132">The amount of expenditures drawn from the state budget is influenced primarily by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the final decision on granting asylum, as well as their state of health.</seg>
<seg id="133">The growing number of people entering the asylum process has a direct impact on the higher uptake of statutory benefits for applicants, such as food, pocket money, basic material equipment, other material equipment and other social contributions.</seg>
<seg id="134">The amount of some selected benefits is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="135">In the Czech Republic, in the audited period, the meal allowance was CZK 58 per person per day, out-of-pocket allowance CZK 12 per person per day and CZK 6 per child under 15 years of age.</seg>
<seg id="136">The costs per asylum seeker per day of stay were on average CZK 351 in 2001, CZK 383 in 2002 and CZK 345 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="137">In addition to the out-of-pocket allowance, asylum seekers accommodated in self-catering accommodation centers and privately accommodated applicants outside asylum facilities may be granted a contribution up to the subsistence level.</seg>
<seg id="138">Act No. 325/1999 Coll., On asylum, as amended, grants, among other things, in § 84 to municipalities the right to a contribution to cover costs incurred in connection with an asylum facility in its territory.</seg>
<seg id="139">The amount of the contribution was determined annually by government resolutions and in the audited period was CZK 7 per person per day of stay.</seg>
<seg id="140">At the same time, municipalities are granted the right to a contribution to cover the non-investment costs of primary schools attended by asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="141">The amount of the contribution in the audited period was CZK 120 per pupil and month, provided that in the given month the person in question attended school for at least 10 days.</seg>
<seg id="142">In the Slovak Republic, in the audited period, the meal allowance was SKK 70 per person per day, out-of-pocket allowance SKK 12 per person per day and SKK 8 per child under 15 years of age.</seg>
<seg id="143">The costs per asylum seeker per day of stay were on average SKK 442 in 2001, SKK 447 in 2002 and SKK 445 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="144">In accordance with Act No. 480/2002 Coll., On Asylum, municipalities in whose territory an asylum facility is located are provided with a contribution for partial reimbursement of expenses incurred by the municipality in connection with the establishment and operation of an asylum facility.</seg>
<seg id="145">So far, municipalities have only partially used the opportunity to apply for a contribution, which is set at SKK 1,500 per bed and calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="146">National legislation in both countries sets a 90-day period for issuing an asylum decision from the commencement of the asylum procedure, and at the same time allows for an extension of this period in justified cases.</seg>
<seg id="147">The most common reason for extending the asylum procedure, which affects the amount of state budget expenditures, is the filing of appeals against decisions not to grant asylum.</seg>
<seg id="148">In the Czech Republic, the highest number of final decisions was issued in the interval between 90 and 180 days (31.54%).</seg>
<seg id="149">The second highest number was within 90 days from the date of submitting the application for asylum (17.61%).</seg>
<seg id="150">In total, 73% of asylum proceedings initiated in 2001-2003 were finally decided within one year of their initiation.</seg>
<seg id="151">Within a period of two years from the commencement of the asylum procedure, 92% of the asylum applications were finally decided.</seg>
<seg id="152">In the Slovak Republic, according to the data of the Municipal Office, up to 90% of applicants who have not been granted asylum use the statutory possibility of extending the time limit by filing an appeal with a court.</seg>
<seg id="153">In some cases, it was an extension of more than a year, and the court proceedings were not closed at the time of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="154">Some contribution to the shortening of the asylum procedure is expected from the establishment of joint offices of the Municipal Office and the Border and Alien Police Office of the Police Force in the reception centers in Adamov-Gbelo, Opatovská Nová Ves and Liptovský Vlachy, which took place at the time of inspection from 1.10.2004.</seg>
<seg id="155">This presupposes a simplification of procedures and a shortening of the time limits for proceedings between the two components of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="156">5. Asylum facilities</seg>
<seg id="157">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic have set up asylum facilities in which they have gradually created suitable conditions for the provision of services to participants in asylum proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="158">During the stay, asylum seekers are provided with accommodation, meals, health care, pocket and basic material equipment and hygiene needs.</seg>
<seg id="159">At the same time, courses are organized as part of leisure activities and conditions are created for applicants for cultural and sports activities.</seg>
<seg id="160">5.1 Asylum facilities in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="161">SUZ manages and operates asylum facilities and is competent to manage state property in the areas of the reception center Vyšní Lhoty, reception and residence center Červený Újezd, residence centers Bělá-Jezová, Zastávka u Brna, Kostelec nad Orlicí, Havířov and in the buildings of integration asylum centers Jaroměř and Stop near Brno.</seg>
<seg id="162">At the beginning of 2002, a reception center was established in the transit area of ​​Prague-Ruzyně Airport.</seg>
<seg id="163">SUZ also ensures the operation of asylum facilities in Stráž pod Ralskem, Seč, Bruntál, Zbýšov and Kašava, which are operated by a legal entity on the basis of Section 80 (3) of Act No. 325/1999 Coll., On Asylum.</seg>
<seg id="164">The total accommodation capacity of the reception centers is 747 places and the total accommodation capacity of the residence centers is 1,977 places.</seg>
<seg id="165">Reception centers are closed facilities that asylum seekers may not leave until the prescribed medical examinations and basic reception procedures specified in Act No. 325/1999 Coll., On Asylum, have been performed.</seg>
<seg id="166">Violation of the obligation to stay in the reception center is considered a misdemeanor.</seg>
<seg id="167">The accommodation centers to which asylum seekers come from the reception centers are used to accommodate asylum seekers until the decision on their application for granting or not granting asylum takes legal effect.</seg>
<seg id="168">Under certain conditions, asylum seekers have the opportunity to leave the residential centers, or to stay in private.</seg>
<seg id="169">Asylum seekers shall be entitled to free accommodation, meals, other services and out-of-pocket expenses at reception and residence centers where they are registered, provided that they have undergone the necessary steps to establish their financial and financial situation, and such conditions shall be that they cannot be fairly demanded of even partial payment for the said services.</seg>
<seg id="170">Integration asylum centers are used for temporary accommodation of persons who have been granted asylum.</seg>
