<seg id="223">Expenditure on security services accounted for more than 10% and expenditure on food purchases from 3.92% to 7.20%.</seg>
<seg id="224">Another significant part was represented by expenditures for accommodation and catering services with a share from 10.82% to 26.96%.</seg>
<seg id="225">A relatively low share in the range from 1.03% to 6.25% was accounted for by capital expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="226">6.2 Identified deficiencies</seg>
<seg id="227">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic pointed out some similar shortcomings which did not have a significant impact on the management of state funds and property.</seg>
<seg id="228">These were shortcomings in particular in the following areas: a) the use of state budget funds contrary to the purpose for which they were intended by the State Budget Act, when actions having the character of technical improvement of tangible fixed assets were covered from current expenditures; b) violation of the Act on Accounting in the field of inventories and non-compliance with the indicative chart of accounts.</seg>
<seg id="229">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the management of state property, when it was left for use to another person without a proper contract; the Act on the Real Estate Cadastre was violated by failing to meet the deadline for reporting changes to the data of the Real Estate Cadastre; by leaving the waste for disposal to a person who was not a person authorized to dispose of waste, the Waste Act was violated.</seg>
<seg id="230">In the Slovak Republic, shortcomings were also found in the provision of disproportionately high advances for electricity and natural gas consumption, shortcomings in the award of public contracts and in the management of state property, when its registration was not sufficiently ensured and the method of disposal of unnecessary assets was not proven.</seg>
<seg id="231">7. Internal control system</seg>
<seg id="232">In the Czech Republic, as of 1.7. In 2002, an internal control system was introduced in the sense of the provisions of Act No. 320/2001 Coll., On financial control, determining the competencies of individual employees responsible for performing preliminary, ongoing and subsequent control.</seg>
<seg id="233">At the same time, an internal audit system was introduced and the internal auditor of SUZ was appointed.</seg>
<seg id="234">Every year, SUZ issues a plan of financial, social and operational technical inspections, the aim of which is a comprehensive verification of the management of financial resources and state property in individual asylum facilities managed by SUZ.</seg>
<seg id="235">In 2002, 42 management checks were carried out and in 2003 54 were carried out.</seg>
<seg id="236">In the Slovak Republic, the direct performance of control activities in the departments and organizations of the Ministry of the Interior of the Slovak Republic in terms of compliance with generally binding legal regulations and internal regulations is ensured by the Office of Control of the Minister.</seg>
<seg id="237">Within the audited period, no control of the fulfillment of tasks in the area of ​​asylum policy was performed.</seg>
<seg id="238">The internal control system of the Municipal Authority is focused primarily on the implementation of preliminary and ongoing financial control pursuant to Act No. 502/2001 Coll., On Financial Control and Internal Audit.</seg>
<seg id="239">The performance of financial control is also regulated by the internal regulations of the Director of the Municipal Authority.</seg>
<seg id="240">The factual focus of control activities as part of the management of individual departments was set within the annual plan of the Municipal Authority.</seg>
<seg id="241">The directors of the unions were appointed to be responsible for carrying out inspections in this area.</seg>
<seg id="242">According to the written documentation submitted, no deficiencies were identified.</seg>
