<p>
<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel controls on expenditure on the construction of the Prague - Dresden motorway</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">Without the existence of trans-European transport networks, it would be difficult to imagine a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the living standards of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of people and cargo is an important task for the state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">This is a very demanding task, both organizationally and technically, as well as financially.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts for sustainable mobility often and hardly find compromises with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">The construction of transport infrastructure, even thanks to the necessary measures in favor of the environment, is financially demanding.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considered procedures and decisions of the state administration in the preparation and acquisition of transport constructions can bring significant savings of public financial resources, which can be used differently for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of control institutions is to actively look for shortcomings that have led to lower than achievable economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditures on transport infrastructure constructions.</seg>
<seg id="11">The control institutions should not only draw the attention of the state administration to the identified shortcomings, but also recommend measures that will lead to an improvement of the situation, for the benefit of the citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as Germany and the Czech Republic), the Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as “BRH”) and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as “SAO”) carried out parallel audits of Dresden (motorway D 8 in the Czech Republic and motorway A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The motorways are connected by a border bridge, which is co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to the cooperation with the SAO, the BRH was able to carry out a thorough control of the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">On the basis of close cooperation with the BRH, the SAO obtained the necessary data on the amount of German costs for bridges and tunnels for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded an agreement on the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the progress of the construction, the completion date was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the award of the contract, the Directorate of Roads and Motorways of the Czech Republic (hereinafter "ŘSD") made mistakes that led to an extension of the competition period and a shortening of the construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was thus signed later than expected.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, the ŘSD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of joint inspection work, the prices of bridges on the D 8 and A 17 motorways were compared, based on the conversion per m2 of bridge structure area.</seg>
<seg id="24">Statistical analysis of prices made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per m2 of area.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in the group of large bridges with a length of over 100 meters.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to the delay that occurred during the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">In analyzing the costs of tunnel construction, the inspectors found that the prices of tunnels on the D 8 motorway are significantly higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">The BRH and the SAO now have a database of bridge and tunnel prices, which they will be able to rely on for future checks on the effectiveness of the funds used for transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, both inspection institutions recommend: standardization of bridge constructions and the use of composite steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where prestressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The main features of the cooperation were her team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel inspection, the inspectors shared their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report informs about the course and results of parallel inspections of funds spent on the construction of a motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The inspections focused on the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the incurred expenses.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel inspections were performed by the BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel inspections took place in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO inspected the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditures in the amount of approximately CZK 20 billion including VAT (approximately € 690 million) on the border section of the D 8 motorway, which has the number 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, € 64 million from European funds (ISPA) was planned to be used.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to the parallel inspection carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH inspected the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A 17 motorway amounted to around € 670 million, of which € 277 million will be co-financed by European funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The motorway from Prague to Dresden is part of the trans-European transport corridor IV. Dresden - Central and Southern Part of Eastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 motorway leads from Prague via Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">The A 17 motorway leads from the Czech / German state border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, the border sections of both motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections were put into operation on December 21, 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is completed as far as Dresden, while on the Czech side the D 8 motorway is not completed, because the section No. 0805 in the length of 16.4 km through the Bohemian Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosice is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, section No. 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of ​​České středohoří.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to forecasts made in the Czech Republic in 2001, the traffic intensity in 2008 at the border section No. 0807 of the D 8 motorway should be 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, in 2010 the intensity of traffic on the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded an Agreement between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic on the connection of the German A 17 motorway and the Czech D 8 motorway at the common state border by the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both states are involved in the construction of the bridge, so the inspection of the construction of this bridge was an important aspect of the parallel inspections carried out by both inspection institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between the BRH and the SAO</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2005, the two Supreme Audit Institutions have been negotiating close cooperation in inspecting the construction of the motorway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both parties had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany contributes financially to the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction is based on ŘSD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to inspect this construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds had been used economically in terms of the overall level of costs for bridges and tunnels on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to ensure the effectiveness of expenditure, taking into account the main technical parameters of the motorway, in particular the layout of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same quality of driving on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the Agreement on the Coordinated Inspection of the D 8 / A Motorway 17 was signed on 4 January 2006 by the Presidents of the two Supreme Audit Institutions.</seg>
<seg id="64">Joint working meetings of the BRH and SAO inspectors took place throughout 2006 at intervals of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">The negotiations addressed current issues and tasks, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from the inspection of the construction of the border bridge and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">An important feature of the cooperation was the continuous exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH performed most of the work on comparing the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and the tender procedure, the SAO largely prepared a methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable legal norms for control in the state administration differ in both countries in the way of closing control actions.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two SAIs have drawn their own audit conclusions on their findings obtained during their audits.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results obtained in the parallel inspections.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will end with the signing of the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of a border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In a 2000 agreement, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed on a date for the completion of the construction of the border bridge, if possible in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="74">The two parties then agreed to postpone this deadline until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">ŘSD acted as investor.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany contributes 42.13% financially to the construction of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the ŘSD proposed that the border bridge should have a prestressed reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, ŘSD approved a composite steel-concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">This decision was justified by the reduction in the number of double pillars from seven to five and the consequent environmental benefits of such a solution for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, comparative calculations performed by ŘSD stated that a composite steel-concrete structure should be a less expensive option.</seg>
<seg id="81">But there was an error in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">It stated that the new composite steel-concrete structure would be only 397 m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it is 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award of the contract for the border bridge, the ŘSD made serious mistakes.</seg>
<seg id="85">It did not prepare the tender dossier, which would adequately describe the criteria for assessment and partial criteria for comparing tenders.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error led to the evaluation and evaluation committee and the Director-General evaluating the tenders subjectively and in a problematic manner.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful tenderer challenged the results of the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">A subsequent investigation by the Office for the Protection of Competition resulted in the construction contract being signed later than originally envisaged.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the summer construction season of 2004, after evaluating the bids, was wasted and the time set aside for construction was shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time, but at the cost of a substantial increase in costs.</seg>
<seg id="91">The offered procedure included double assembly of the bridge superstructure, a change in the construction of the pillars and the establishment and equipment of assembly spaces.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the construction company was not able to obtain the originally designed type of steel in the required time.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel - at a price higher by about € 4 million, which had to be paid in full by ŘSD - made it possible to shorten the time for anti-corrosion protection, which subsequently made it possible to shorten the total construction time of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of € 18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of building the border bridge will increase significantly due to the accelerated procedure and other adjustments in funding.</seg>
<seg id="95">The reduced time set aside for construction work has led to a price increase of around € 5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">At present, the amount of net costs is around € 25.9 million, without taking into account the automatic increase in prices (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">The two supreme audit institutions analyzed the prices of bridges on the D 8 and A 17 motorways in order to identify bridges whose price was too high and to compare the prices of bridges on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis was based on methods of mathematical statistics.</seg>
<seg id="100">Furthermore, the tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on motorways in Germany (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on the A 17 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="102">In preparing this part of the inspection, it was important to accurately identify the relevant prices.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two Supreme Audit Institutions have established the following principles for comparing bridge prices: based on the actual price paid for the bridge without value added tax (VAT rates differ in the Czech Republic and the SNR and are subject to change); disregard prices for special bridge foundations; convert prices in CZK to € according to the rate of the European Central Bank valid as of 30 December 2005 (CZK 29 = € 1).</seg>
<seg id="104">On D 8 and A 17 there are bridges of various constructions (steel-concrete, prestressed reinforced concrete, composite steel-concrete and steel) and various sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In an effort to ensure the homogeneity of the examined structures, the bridges were divided into groups according to the type of structure.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyzes.</seg>
<seg id="107">By far the most common type of structure was concrete bridges on both sides of the border (20 bridges on the D 8, 36 bridges on the A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis focused mainly on this group of bridges, as the size of the set allowed the use of mathematical-statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The inspections revealed that the prices per m 2 of concrete bridges on D 8 and A 17 depend on the size of the bridge (its length, area): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the price dependence on size was stronger than for Czech bridges (see graphs below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges on the A 17 and four on the D 8 have been identified, the price of which is significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">To find these bridges, a method was used to determine atypical values ​​in a set of numbers, as well as a regression analysis taking into account the dependence of the bridge price on its size (to determine atypically expensive bridges, the standard distance from the regression curve is upwards).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information on the atypically high price of these bridges should only be considered as an indicator of which bridges to focus on.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the causes of the high price in each identified case should be analyzed.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative measures, or environmental protection requirements or other acceptable reasons.</seg>
<seg id="116">Given that Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than German ones (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the price of a bridge on its length could lead to the assumption that Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The hypothesis of lower prices of Czech concrete bridges is also supported by lower labor costs in the construction industry in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">On the contrary, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges on the D 8 are higher than on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During the joint negotiations, two possible causes of this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional companies to participate in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of a contract for a part of a motorway route that is several kilometers long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized companies do not participate in such a competition because the contract is too large for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic there is greater variability in the construction of bridges than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of bridge construction was decided long before its construction.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision is made at the time when the ŘSD translates the application for a zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this time, the ŘSD selects bridge types from several variants, but economy plays a smaller role in decision-making.</seg>
<seg id="130">A general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could be expressed only on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction market in both countries, which, however, would go beyond the scope of this inspection.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive composite steel-concrete bridge on the D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, it was found that the prices of tunnels on the D 8 are twice as high as tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the main construction and technical parameters of the D 8 tunnels with the tunnels in Germany did not show any significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the Czech Republic in the field of tunnel construction.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow general conclusions to be drawn.</seg>
<seg id="136">Efficiency and effectiveness of the construction of the Dresden - Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was established in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government approved a concept for the development of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D 8 motorway was to be gradually extended from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section No. 0805 across the Bohemian Central Mountains was to be acquired before the border section No. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic acquires the D 8 motorway as part of program financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">In the program No. 327 220 "Construction of the D 8 motorway Prague - Ústí nad Labem - state border of the Czech Republic / Germany" two goals were set for the construction of the D 8 motorway:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">to improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem - a national goal;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">to improve the connection between Prague and Berlin within the framework of IV. trans-European transport corridor Berlin-Istanbul - international destination.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the program, the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains was to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section No. 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be added here that the completion date is not identical to the commissioning date.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains is now in the stage of an official zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists have challenged the decision with lawsuits.</seg>
<seg id="151">There is no final decision on the actions.</seg>
<seg id="152">Therefore, it cannot be ruled out that the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains will be completed several years later than stated in the program documentation.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed postponing the completion date of section No. 0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of the above facts, the construction of the border section did not reach the national goal - improving the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">ŘSD performed an estimate of capital expenditures for the border section D 8 No. 0807 and section No. 0805 across the Bohemian Central Mountains in the years 1999 - 2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimated investment costs included in these capital expenditures are around € 639 million together for both sections 0805 and 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the economic assessment (EIRR = internal rate of return)</seg>
<seg id="158">All considered motorways and expressways open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">In the northern part of the border section, the intensity of traffic was 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="160">All considered motorways and expressways open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">In the northern part of the border section, the intensity of traffic was 22,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="162">All considered motorways and expressways open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">In the northern part of the border section, the intensity of traffic was 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and the section across the Bohemian Central Mountains will be completed on time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the inspection, however, it is clear that the section across the Bohemian Central Mountains will not be open in the original term.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the above EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">Costs for both sections excluding VAT, calculated as at 31 December 2005, were € 897 million, ie 27.4% higher than the level of costs used in the economic analysis in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">However, there is a risk that section 0805 will be run on another, more expensive route, which would affect the above-mentioned economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="169">The economic analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically viable with a traffic intensity of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 was 22,940 vehicles, but a study addressing the issue of detours for the missing section through the Czech Central Highlands envisages a traffic intensity of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day, which pushes the investment below the limit of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="171">With a higher load of detours for the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains, there is a high probability of congestion, and thus an increase in external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The above-mentioned reduction in revenues and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR that the construction of the border section D 8 should have had will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is therefore inefficient.</seg>
<seg id="174">Also during the construction of the A 17 motorway, the costs were exceeded in a similar way as in the case of these two sections on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the federal road development plan for long-distance transport for 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany estimated the cost of around € 320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting cost / income ratio was then 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, costs have risen sharply to around € 670 million, reducing the cost / income ratio by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to the parallel inspection carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH inspected the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">At the same time, the BRH found that the competent state approval authority required an off-road tunnel for the third section A 17, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the inspection, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the German Road Construction Administration that a tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">The result was savings that amounted to around € 10 million in construction costs alone and € 0.15 million in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">During the assessment of the first section A 17 BRH found that the construction project was not properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">The following example illustrates this:</seg>
<seg id="184">In the preparatory stage, the road construction administration did not carry out a survey of the bedrock conditions in the Dölzschen rocks, as the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was done only after the tunnel boring machine hit a rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests have shown that the rocks are more weathered inside than expected during the tender.</seg>
<seg id="187">Therefore, costly measures had to be taken, such as mooring, grouting and stone fall protection nets, which required around € 3.3 million.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Directorate of Roads and Motorways had to bear the costs not only of other emergency operations, such as safety measures in the Dölzschen rocks, but also measures that would not be necessary if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes costs related to the interruption of construction operations (€ 3.2 million), further training of drilling staff (€ 0.5 million) and rising wages and expenditure on goods due to the project being exceeded (€ 7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overrun thus amounted to approximately € 10.7 million, which did not correspond to any added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">Based on the lessons learned from this and other audited projects, the BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter management in its supervision of road construction work.</seg>
<seg id="192">At the same time, the Federal Ministry should give the Roads and Motorways Directorates the necessary impetus to implement quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for the BRH and the SAO The cooperation fulfilled the intention of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained control knowledge about the preparation, assignment and course of construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">The two Supreme Audit Institutions have set up a database of bridge and tunnel prices on which future inspections can be based.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main construction and technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and the route of the D 8 motorway do not differ from the parameters of A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The inspectors of both institutions participating in the cooperation gained new experience, which they can use in further inspections.</seg>
</p>
