<p>
<seg id="1">Procurement of construction work and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel audits carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the public and private sectors.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources as efficiently and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor in the success of the Single Economic Space.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU has set limits in its regulations above which a contracting authority must meet certain requirements to guarantee a wide and unrestricted competitive environment throughout the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose and put European procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">The Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts that are below the EU limits in value, the regulation of their award remains within the competence of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In addition, public procurement is prone to corruption with consequent high potential for harm.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting authorities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair favoritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits in the area of ​​procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in buildings and transport structures.</seg>
<seg id="14">The cooperation was also focused on the area of ​​European procurement law as it was transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The inspections also included the award of contracts below European limits in order to cover the area of ​​corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two SAIs are summarized in a joint report addressed, inter alia, to international organizations such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and controlled institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH assessment is based on comprehensive inspections of the above-mentioned areas, which were carried out by the German building administrations responsible for federal transport and civil engineering in the years 2011 to 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, the construction of motorways and large-scale building construction projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH also included findings from previous inspections in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's evaluation is based on inspections carried out during the years 2008 to 2012, which focused on the construction of roads, railways, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other structures in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, federal public procurement is mostly carried out by the state building administrations.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, state institutions for road and railway construction are responsible for awarding public contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of building construction, the award of public contracts is carried out by entities that are recipients of budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used in the individual phases of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation must take into account the differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">The structure of the law on public procurement in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany are governed by budgetary law and the relevant administrative acts.</seg>
<seg id="30">The internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details concerning the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called federal government procurement manuals, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail with regard to legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the award of public contracts is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legal regulations that apply to contracts with a value above and below European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The contracting law underwent significant changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened up space for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption during the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As far as European procurement procedures are concerned, open and restricted procedures in particular need to be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European threshold are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for tenders, restricted call for tenders, negotiated procedure), but these are practically identical to the above conditions for European tenders.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterized by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public invitations to participate (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and in the invitation to participate in the competition, the tender may be submitted by any interested party.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved primarily by dividing the total public contract into commercially specific parts and dividing it into partial contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">By awarding contracts divided into these parts, it is given a chance to participate in the procedure by as many interested parties as possible.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German contract law are time-tested tools for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are registered in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, it is necessary to apply the conditions of European procedures also in cases of awarding public contracts with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception is the simplified sub-limit procedure, where the contracting authority may use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which a contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favorable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">Current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between open and restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 registered construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">The total volume of contracting authorities' contracts for public works and the share of individual types of proceedings in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction work in Germany amounted to 7,675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">CZK, of which CZK 1,138 billion (15%) accounted for the share of public contracts, which, in addition to contracts awarded by the federal government, also included contracts awarded by individual federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of federal road and building projects (excluding the construction of railways and waterworks) reached CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal contracts for civil engineering and transport construction was as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public calls; 12.7% restricted procedures and restricted calls;</seg>
<seg id="55">6.6% negotiated procedures and direct award of contracts; 33.2% is the share of European tenders.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic in 2011 reached CZK 118.6 billion, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, it reached the value of CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of types of procurement procedures in 2011: 65.1% open procedures; 14.3% restricted procedure; 9.5% negotiated procedure; 8.4% simplified procedures for sub-threshold contracts; 2.7% other proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="59">The figures include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">These figures show that: parallel controls in both countries focused on a substantial part of public procurement procedures; the prevention of corruption, which must always be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open meaning. Procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and the BRH carried out parallel inspections of the award of European works contracts with an emphasis on the prevention of corruption in their countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The inspections focused on the comparison of legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public procurement in the field of land and transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">Here are the key findings:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national law of both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Prevention of corruption is not only the goal of the EU directive, but the national procurement rules of both countries, which differ in part in terms of focus and detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the basic requirement that the tender dossier must meet is the inclusion of all the information needed to prepare tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specification must be neutral and must not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The tender documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, the problem is the insufficient definition of the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, the division of contracts into lots is required where possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement is complied with in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO's inspections have shown that in the Czech Republic, considerable volumes of public works are awarded in the field of road construction, without being divided into parts, or they are divided, but only into very significant parts in terms of volume. This can distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">These limitations on market potential can result in significant cost increases and create the risk of frivolous price negotiations and inadmissible agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">Legislation in both countries allows contracting authorities, under certain conditions, to subcontract further construction work if this need arises only after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for the correct determination of the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, according to the valid regulations, contracting authorities are free to determine one of the open procurement procedures, namely open procedure or restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">German procurement and budgetary law gives priority to open procedures for both European tenders and national tenders, known as public invitations to tender.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open procurement procedures in both countries allow a wider range of bidders to submit a bid and also reduce the risk of corruption, as they make it difficult to negotiate prices illegally between bidders.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best results are achieved in the area of ​​value for money.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts whose estimated total price reaches or exceeds the limits set by the EU, the audited contracting authorities always issued a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">In determining the type of procurement procedure, the correct determination of the estimated value of the contract plays a very important role.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used to objectively determine the price of public works, in which the values ​​are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective tool.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the field of road construction, but they are not yet an effective tool (Section 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract under European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish prior information and a call for tenders in order to strengthen competition by enabling candidates to prepare in time for tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and / or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">There is a greater risk of manipulation when selecting candidates for participation in a restricted tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee real competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria must be objective, non-discriminatory and published well in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to EU requirements, contracting authorities in both countries should, as often as possible, rotate candidates who are invited to participate in the selection process when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, the requirements for risk prevention are partly very detailed.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting authorities did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (section 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting authorities must ensure during the procurement procedure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between these candidates and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must be avoided as far as possible so as not to restrict competition by means of illegal agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the relevant measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the German contracting authorities inspected did not comply with this requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements for labeling, documentation, protection and confidentiality of tenders are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Inspections in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (section 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of tenders is procedurally regulated in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more complex, but have not always been respected by the inspected contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting authorities have forwarded their tenders to third parties for inspection without prior assessment, without duly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">The tenders were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulations (point 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">Due to the legal protection of the enterprises, the participants must be informed about the intended award of the contract before the latter is finalized.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule is also designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in a few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The tender documentation was not always complete or completely credible for the audited contracting authorities in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level were not always properly respected in the minutes.</seg>
<seg id="113">In addition, some of the identified shortcomings reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting authorities in both countries mostly fulfilled their reporting obligations (section 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the main principles of European procurement law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European contract law</seg>
<seg id="117">To ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union have adopted, inter alia, a directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts to ensure the free movement of goods and services and a directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to review procedures. in the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (Review Procedures Directive), the two directives were to be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The EU's general procurement principles include in particular: the requirement for a competitive environment; the requirement of equal treatment or non-discrimination; transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include The Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public contracts also includes provisions for construction projects with a total estimated value of € 5 million or more.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions affect: the content of the tender dossier; the type of procurement procedure used; disclosure of certain information before, during and after the proceedings; meeting the deadline for receipt of tenders; qualification requirements that may be required of candidates; criteria for selecting the most suitable tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">The legal protection of candidates is governed by the Review Procedures Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of the contract award law, tenderers may have the contracting authority's decision reviewed in accordance with the examination procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries have transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="126">In neither country is there a legal definition of what corruption actually means.</seg>
<seg id="127">Corruption is generally understood as the abuse of personal (confidential) status for one's own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is encouraged by those who benefit.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the total damage related to corruption amounts to 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="132">If a contracting authority is involved in the contract, conventions restricting competition or allowing unfair practices may undermine confidence in the integrity, ability and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Therefore, the prevention of corruption is a crucial task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">Practices and procedures must be monitored, especially in areas particularly prone to corruption, so that adequate measures can be taken to prevent them.</seg>
