<seg id="372">Prior notices are required for projects where the total cost estimate is equal to or greater than the European limit and where the contracting authority wishes to shorten the deadline for submission of tenders in individual procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="373">The contracting authority is obliged to publish a contract notice with detailed information for all public contracts that require a European procedure.</seg>
<seg id="374">The information is binding for the contracting authority after publication.</seg>
<seg id="375">The notification must include, inter alia, the specifications, the time limits for the procedure and for completing the contract, the specific requirements and the selection criteria and their weights.</seg>
<seg id="376">A common vocabulary for public procurement must be used to describe the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="377">Preliminary information and contract notices are published in the EU in the Official Journal of the EU and on the contracting authority's profile.</seg>
<seg id="378">In order to prevent discrimination against foreign candidates, notices at national level should not contain any additional information and should not be published before the text of the notification is sent to the Publications Office of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="379">Incomplete or inaccurate information in the pre-notification may distort competition or even facilitate manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="380">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="381">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="382">Both countries have fully implemented EU provisions on prior information and procurement notices into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="383">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="384">In the Czech Republic, preliminary information and notices must also be published in the case of contracts for which a European procedure is not required.</seg>
<seg id="385">The procurement procedure may not start earlier than one month after the dispatch of the prior notice.</seg>
<seg id="386">Disclosure of prior information may be waived only in exceptional cases.</seg>
<seg id="387">In Germany, prior information is not required in cases where a European procedure is not required.</seg>
<seg id="388">In the case of national proceedings, the public call must be published on the federal government's website and, where appropriate, in the press.</seg>
<seg id="389">In the case of restricted procedures without competition from participants, the notice must be published if the estimated price of the contract is equal to or higher than € 25,000 (CZK 625 thousand).</seg>
<seg id="390">Preliminary notices must explain all planned parts of the project.</seg>
<seg id="391">This is an important requirement given the number of small contracts in Germany.</seg>
