<seg id="393">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="394">BRH</seg>
<seg id="395">Prior notice</seg>
<seg id="396">The contracting authorities published a prior notice of projects which included works to be awarded in a European procedure.</seg>
<seg id="397">In some open procedures, they shortened the deadline, although the number of days between sending the pre-notification and sending the contract notice was less than 52 days.</seg>
<seg id="398">In the case of other summary proceedings, the annual deadlines for prior information have expired and should be renewed.</seg>
<seg id="399">In many cases, the prior notification did not indicate the expected division of the works into several parts.</seg>
<seg id="400">Notice of the opening of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="401">Some notifications contained codes from a common dictionary that deviated from the content of the pre-notification or did not specify exactly the work to be carried out.</seg>
<seg id="402">In rare cases, notices at national level included more information, eg on deadlines, or were published before the notice was published in the Official Journal of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="403">Ex-ante transparency</seg>
<seg id="404">One contracting authority hired an external company to publish the national notice.</seg>
<seg id="405">It published a notice on its platform, the use of which was charged.</seg>
<seg id="406">However, the contracting authority did not check whether this company had to comply with the requirement to forward the notification to a free internet government portal.</seg>
<seg id="407">The sample found that only a third of the announcements were actually published on the government portal.</seg>
<seg id="408">SAO</seg>
<seg id="409">Notice of the opening of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="410">During the construction of the wastewater treatment plant, the contracting authority did not set out in the notice of the restricted tender to the construction contractor the criteria according to which it will reduce the large number of tenders for the evaluation procedure.</seg>
<seg id="411">The contracting authority was not able to document the method of selection (reduction) of tenders for evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="412">The reduction in the number of offers was made possible by previous legislation.</seg>
<seg id="413">During the construction of the ring road, the contracting authority for one construction did not define in the notice of initiation of the restricted procedure or in the qualification documentation the values ​​according to which it will assess the degree of fulfillment of qualification criteria or the number of candidates to be invited.</seg>
<seg id="414">The contracting authority assessed the fulfillment of the qualification in such a way that all six candidates in the restricted procedure fulfilled it, but excluded one of them, stating that they fulfilled only in the last sixth place.</seg>
<seg id="415">The contracting authority's procedure was not transparent, as it did not publish information in advance on what of the qualification data will be evaluated and how.</seg>
<seg id="416">Publication of calls</seg>
<seg id="417">In violation of the law, the contracting authority did not publish a written invitation to submit tenders for construction modifications in former military districts.</seg>
<seg id="418">Conclusions and recommendations / summary</seg>
<seg id="419">A two-stage information process with prior information and publication of a notice of initiation is an important tool for meeting the requirements of transparency and strengthening the competitive environment applied in European proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="420">By extending the obligation to publish prior information in the Czech Republic for national procurement procedures as well, and strengthening this obligation in Germany for limited procedures, both countries have increased the transparency of procurement procedures and improved the competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="421">Selection of candidates in restricted procedures</seg>
<seg id="422">Unlike open procedures, restricted procedures do not allow all potential tenderers to participate.</seg>
<seg id="423">In restricted procedures, the contracting authority first selects potential suppliers who will be asked to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="424">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="425">EU provisions allow limiting the number of applicants in European restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="426">However, the restricted procedure requires at least five tenderers who will be invited to submit a tender, and in the case of a negotiated procedure with publication, at least three potential tenderers must be invited.</seg>
<seg id="427">In any case, the number of candidates invited must be wide enough to guarantee real competition.</seg>
<seg id="428">The selection criteria must be objective and non-discriminatory and must be published in advance.</seg>
<seg id="429">The selection of potential candidates who will be invited is very prone to manipulation, eg by the preferences of some of them.</seg>
<seg id="430">Reducing competition to a few bidders can facilitate their collusion.</seg>
<seg id="431">This has a negative impact on the outcome of the proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="432">Therefore, the contracting authority must take measures to prevent manipulation and ensure that it has effective control so that this procedure is transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="433">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="434">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="435">The provisions for the selection of candidates are similar in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="436">In addition to the requirements of the European Directive, contracting authorities should vary the tenders they invite to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="437">It is also not permissible to restrict competition from a regional point of view.</seg>
<seg id="438">Contracting authorities must document and justify the selection of tenderers and the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="439">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="440">In Germany, at least three candidates are required to be invited in the case of a restricted procedure and several suitable candidates in the case of a negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="441">With the exception of two cases, the new Czech regulations do not allow limiting the number of candidates addressed in the case of restricted and negotiated procedures.</seg>
<seg id="442">In Germany, the "four eyes" principle must be respected when selecting candidates.</seg>
<seg id="443">While one worker proposes a list of them, another must substantially modify the proposal, eg by deleting the proposed candidate or substituting another.</seg>
<seg id="444">This is to prevent a situation where an individual can definitively determine the circle of candidates who will take part in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="445">In the absence of such a provision, far-reaching illegal agreement between the participants is possible.</seg>
<seg id="446">The list of candidates who will be invited to submit a tender must be confidential and must not be disclosed.</seg>
<seg id="447">Authorized independent experts are also obliged to do so.</seg>
<seg id="448">There is no similar measure or measure for the confidential treatment of the list of candidates in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="449">According to German provisions, they may not nominate candidates from an external company, but may make proposals to the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="450">There is no similar requirement in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="451">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="452">BRH</seg>
<seg id="453">Number of applicants</seg>
<seg id="454">Except for a few cases, the requirement to address the minimum number of applicants was met.</seg>
<seg id="455">The analysis of almost 7,000 contracts for constructions with a value up to the national limit showed that in the case of limited procedures, the contracting authorities invited an average of 6.6 potential bidders and in the case of direct negotiated procedures on average 4.4 bidders.</seg>
<seg id="456">Change of suppliers and regional restrictions</seg>
<seg id="457">The contracting authorities, especially in the area of ​​building construction, did not change the circle of candidates addressed, as they had good experience with those with whom they had worked so far.</seg>
<seg id="458">THIS segment IS intentionally LEFT blank</seg>
<seg id="459">The contracting authorities argued that, in the case of a closed procedure, they should ensure that they contact candidates whose suitability they have already ascertained in advance.</seg>
<seg id="460">Although there was no evidence of illegal regional restrictions, the circle of candidates in a closed procedure included a larger proportion of regional candidates than in the case of public proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="461">The contracting authorities explained this by the low amount of the contract compared to the public tender and the high travel costs for potential tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="462">The principle of cross-checking and proposals of self-employed professionals</seg>
<seg id="463">The contracting authorities mostly ignored the obligation to change the list of candidates proposed by self-employed professionals.</seg>
<seg id="464">They argued in particular for lack of staff, time pressure or inadequate knowledge of a suitable candidate.</seg>
<seg id="465">In many cases, it was not clear from the records who proposed the candidate who had been asked to take part in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="466">An inspection of some samples showed that the list of potential candidates was drawn up by self-employed experts and accepted by the contracting authority without changes.</seg>
<seg id="467">Thus, the contracting authorities did not sufficiently protect themselves from potential manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="468">Confidentiality of treatment of lists of potential candidates</seg>
<seg id="469">For one contracting authority, a list of candidates for invitations to tender was kept in a database to which all employees had access at any time.</seg>
<seg id="470">This allowed the manipulation or unauthorized disclosure of the names of the candidates expected or accepted, who could then agree on a price.</seg>
<seg id="471">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="472">The documentation stated the reasons for the selection of candidates in only a few cases.</seg>
<seg id="473">SAO</seg>
<seg id="474">Criteria for selection of candidates</seg>
<seg id="475">During the construction of the ring road, those interested did not have information on what from the data on their qualifications will be evaluated and in what way.</seg>
<seg id="476">For the action related to the development and modernization of waterways and ports, the criteria for limiting the number of tenderers were not set out in the contract notice for participation in the restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="477">All eight tenderers met the qualification requirements, but this exceeded the number to which the contracting authority limited participation in the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="478">The Commission then selected candidates at random - by drawing lots, which was legal at the time.</seg>
<seg id="479">This procedure should have been mentioned as a criterion in the tender notice.</seg>
<seg id="480">Summary</seg>
<seg id="481">In view of the high risk of manipulation in the selection of the winning tenderer in restricted procedures, both countries have introduced special measures to prevent unlawful restrictions of competition.</seg>
<seg id="482">German rules limit such opportunities for manipulation by means of so-called cross-checking (four-eyes principle), by maintaining the confidentiality of the list of candidates and by prohibiting proposals for the selection of candidates from outside companies.</seg>
<seg id="483">The Czech rules aim to prevent potential restrictions with the aim of manipulation mainly by an unlimited number of applicants.</seg>
<seg id="484">However, the audit found that some of these rules were not sufficiently applied and that inadmissible restrictions on the number of candidates were not prevented in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="485">Contracting authorities are obliged to completely eliminate the mentioned shortcomings.</seg>
<seg id="486">Submission of bids</seg>
<seg id="487">The procurement phase, in which potential tenderers may prepare tenders on the basis of the tender dossier they have received, begins with the publication of information on the procurement procedure and / or a call for tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="488">Until the date of opening the envelopes, potential tenderers may submit their tenders to the contracting authority, thus bidding for the contract.</seg>
<seg id="489">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="490">EU law does not prescribe specific requirements at this stage of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="491">The contracting authority must follow the national regulations governing this phase of the procedure and prevent potential manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="492">These regulations apply in particular to the organization and control.</seg>
<seg id="493">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="494">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="495">The principle applies that tender documents, on the basis of which potential suppliers prepare their bids, must always be sent by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="496">Design offices that are interested in management should not fulfill this role.</seg>
<seg id="497">The contracting authority must ensure that all candidates receive the same information during this phase of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="498">In case of ambiguities in the tender documentation or if other questions arise, only the contracting authority may provide information to the tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="499">The design offices responsible for drawing up the tender dossier may not provide any information.</seg>
<seg id="500">Throughout this phase, any contact between the design office and the tenderers must be avoided.</seg>
<seg id="501">They must remain anonymous throughout, as allowing contact with them may adversely affect competition.</seg>
<seg id="502">Tenders sent by post or submitted directly must be submitted in a sealed envelope.</seg>
<seg id="503">Electronically submitted bids must be encrypted.</seg>
<seg id="504">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="505">In Germany, the contracting authority may entrust insured suppliers of external services with the printing and distribution of documentation, and their staff must be bound by professional secrecy.</seg>
<seg id="506">In Germany, tenders received must be marked with the date of receipt and handed over directly and immediately in their original state (sealed) to the official in charge of their storage.</seg>
<seg id="507">This staff member must not be involved in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="508">Received bids must be locked until the date the envelopes are opened.</seg>
<seg id="509">In the Czech Republic, the offers received are marked with a serial number.</seg>
<seg id="510">The contracting authority issues a report with data on the tender, including the number of the tender and information on the preparation of the tender and its receipt.</seg>
<seg id="511">There are no special regulations on the safekeeping of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="512">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="513">BRH</seg>
<seg id="514">BRH checked the assignment of the administrative building.</seg>
<seg id="515">Sending tender documentation</seg>
<seg id="516">The inspected contracting authorities of the construction administration sent the tender documentation either directly or entrusted its printing and distribution to an external company.</seg>
<seg id="517">The self-employed did not send any documentation.</seg>
<seg id="518">Information provided to candidates</seg>
<seg id="519">In the part of the tender documentation concerning inquiries and obtaining information, the contracting authority did not follow the rule for separate planning from the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="520">Contrary to the relevant regulations, he often did not mention the names of his contact staff in the documentation, but rather the staff of the project management department.</seg>
<seg id="521">Some notices in the tender procedure even contained the names of companies or self-employed persons who participated in the preparation of the tender dossier.</seg>
<seg id="522">In rare cases, candidates who asked questions during the procurement procedure did not receive identical information.</seg>
<seg id="523">Labeling of offers</seg>
<seg id="524">For contracting authorities, all accepted tenders were stamped and acknowledged of receipt.</seg>
<seg id="525">However, in some cases in the negotiated procedure, bids were accepted by self-employed professionals, in breach of the one-stop-corruption rule.</seg>
<seg id="526">Custody of the tenders</seg>
<seg id="527">Once marked, not all tenders were passed on directly and without delay to the official assigned to keep them in custody locked the tenders in a steel cabinet.</seg>
<seg id="528">For one contracting authority, tenders were temporarily placed in an open filing cabinet, to which all employees had access.</seg>
<seg id="529">Another contracting authority placed the box in the hallway without constant supervision, and part of the bids thrown in the box remained there overnight.</seg>
<seg id="530">The mailbox opening was wide and unsecured, making it accessible not only to employees.</seg>
<seg id="531">SAO</seg>
<seg id="532">The SAO did not find any shortcomings in this area.</seg>
<seg id="533">Summary</seg>
<seg id="534">In both countries, rules are laid down to prevent contacts, in particular between the companies involved and the design offices cooperating in the procurement procedure, throughout the process.</seg>
<seg id="535">Equal treatment is ensured by sending the same information to all candidates.</seg>
<seg id="536">Rules for the prevention of manipulation and corruption are appropriate for the receipt, safekeeping and confidentiality of offers.</seg>
<seg id="537">In Germany, the relevant requirements are somewhat more elaborated than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="538">In Germany, the accumulated control records showed breaches of the rules in some areas.</seg>
<seg id="539">These discrepancies can be easily remedied.</seg>
<seg id="540">Opening envelopes</seg>
<seg id="541">Opening envelopes</seg>
<seg id="542">During the opening of the envelopes, the offers that have been closed so far are opened, their content is read and published.</seg>
<seg id="543">The period for which the tenderer is bound by his tender begins at the end of the deadline for submission of envelopes or their opening and ends with the deadline specified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="544">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="545">European legislation does not contain any specific provisions dealing with the opening of envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="546">However, national laws and regulations contain extensive requirements for the protection of bids and competition during this sensitive phase of the entire procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="547">The principles of "more eyes", transparency and credibility of the process of opening the envelopes are intended to prevent manipulations and modifications to the tenders already submitted.</seg>
<seg id="548">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="549">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="550">The envelopes must be opened by several persons appointed by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="551">Compliance with the "more eyes" principle is intended to prevent individuals from covertly manipulating offers.</seg>
<seg id="552">Candidates may be present when the envelopes are opened.</seg>
<seg id="553">When opening, all envelopes must be placed in front of the chairman of the commission and are opened one after the other.</seg>
<seg id="554">Late bids may not be considered.</seg>
<seg id="555">To ensure transparency when opening the envelopes, this phase, including the conclusions (results), must be recorded in writing. The record must include, among other things, the names of the tenderers and the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="556">The minutes must be read and signed by the group leader.</seg>
<seg id="557">The minutes may also be signed by the candidates present.</seg>
<seg id="558">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="559">In the Czech Republic, a commission is being set up to open envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="560">The participation of independent experts is allowed.</seg>
<seg id="561">The members of the commission may also be entrusted with the discussion in the subsequent stages of the procedure, ie the evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="562">In Germany, the envelopes are opened in the presence of the manager and the recorder.</seg>
<seg id="563">The manager must be an employee of the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="564">The manager and, in the case of building construction, the recorder may not be participants in the preparatory phase (creation of tender documentation), may not decide on the award of the contract and may not be members in the subsequent processing (management) of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="565">German regulations require that the record of the opening of envelopes contain not only the offer prices, but also all information on discounts and special (unusual) signs, such as damaged envelopes upon receipt or late arrivals.</seg>
<seg id="566">In the Czech Republic, in addition to the offer prices, the registration must also contain information on the language of the offer and the tenderer's signature authorization.</seg>
<seg id="567">German regulations require that all parts of the envelopes to be opened be marked in order to prevent subsequent changes.</seg>
<seg id="568">Tenders, usually marked in the form of a perforation with the date, must be kept confidential after the opening of the envelopes has been closed and may only be made available to persons who further process them.</seg>
<seg id="569">There are no similar measures in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="570">If a single tender is received in the Czech Republic, the envelope must not be opened and the tenderer must be notified immediately.</seg>
<seg id="571">In Germany, they do not have this arrangement, and if a single tender is accepted, it is opened and evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="572">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="573">BRH</seg>
<seg id="574">Principle of cross-checking</seg>
<seg id="575">During the opening of the envelopes, the contracting authorities followed the principle of four eyes.</seg>
<seg id="576">The leader and recorder, who was not assigned a different role, were always present.</seg>
<seg id="577">In rare cases, however, in small negotiated procedures, natural persons opened tenders sent to them without the participation of the contracting authority.</seg>
