<seg id="588">Summary</seg>
<seg id="589">Substantial parts of the provisions on the opening of envelopes are identical in both countries with regard to the principle of "more eyes" and the principle of transparency, and thus make it possible to substantially reduce the risk of corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="590">The German rules are more complex in comparison with the Czech Republic, especially the requirements for accurate documentation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="591">Marking, safe storage and respect for the confidentiality of tenders significantly limit the possibility of subsequent changes in the tenders submitted.</seg>
<seg id="592">In addition, the staff responsible for opening the envelopes may not carry out any other activities related to the contract to be awarded.</seg>
<seg id="593">The findings, despite the detection of some irregularities, confirm that the rules for opening envelopes are largely applied.</seg>
<seg id="594">Assessment and evaluation of offers</seg>
<seg id="595">The contracting authority must examine and evaluate the tenders received within the deadline.</seg>
<seg id="596">At the same time, they must award the contract to the tenderer who best meets the award criteria in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="597">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="598">EU law sets out the process of assessing and evaluating tenders in several steps:</seg>
<seg id="599">The first step is to check the suitability of the candidates.</seg>
<seg id="600">They must have a good economic and financial position and the required professional and technical knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="601">Candidates who have ever been convicted of bribery or fraud must always be excluded from the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="602">Tenders of non-excluded tenderers must be evaluated in terms of numerical accuracy, technical suitability and value for money on the basis of previously published award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="603">The contracting authority must determine the most economically advantageous tender and, in particular, examine all significantly low price tenders.</seg>
<seg id="604">Review and evaluation is particularly sensitive and prone to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, tenderers may be excluded without a valid reason, or tenders that do not meet the requirements may be left in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="606">The result of the evaluation may be incorrectly affected by the preference or disadvantage of a tenderer, which may prevent the selection of the most economically advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="607">The contracting authority must therefore take special measures in selecting the persons involved in the process and must ensure that they meet the requirements of good repute and technical knowledge.</seg>
<seg id="608">It must also make sure that the whole process and the decisions taken are transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="609">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="611">In line with EU requirements, the relevant provisions in both countries require a review and evaluation of tenders in successive steps.</seg>
<seg id="612">During the evaluation, the requirements for proving the suitability of candidates, the evaluation criteria and their weights stated in the notice or in the tender dossier may not be changed.</seg>
<seg id="613">The criteria set for assessing the suitability of candidates may no longer be used.</seg>
<seg id="614">Further evaluation can only be performed on the basis of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="615">The tenders submitted must first be formally examined to see whether they are complete or whether they do not contain suspicious elements that could encourage manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="616">If tenderers are excluded from further examination and evaluation of the tenders submitted by them, they must be informed immediately.</seg>
<seg id="617">If the evaluation of tenders results in a disproportionately low tender price, the tenderer concerned must be given the opportunity to comment on the situation before any tender is rejected.</seg>
<seg id="618">The reasons for the decision must be transparently documented.</seg>
<seg id="619">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="620">In Germany, tenderers must maintain confidentiality and only eligible persons may take part in the evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="621">The mathematical accuracy of the tenders may only be checked by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="622">Only employees who are not involved in the decision-making phase of the supplier selection or in the project implementation phase can be entrusted with the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="623">There are no precise provisions on who can carry out further reviews and evaluations.</seg>
<seg id="624">If external companies are commissioned to review and evaluate tenders, they must be aware that tenders are confidential and honestly respect this fact.</seg>
<seg id="625">They can only make proposals for decisions to the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="626">In the Czech Republic, tenders must be reviewed and evaluated by a commission appointed by the contracting authority, which will draw up a report proposing the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="627">However, in both countries, the final decision depends on the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="628">If, in Germany, the documents and declarations required in connection with the submission of tenders are incomplete, the tenderers concerned must subsequently submit the required documents within six days.</seg>
<seg id="629">THIS segment IS intentionally LEFT blank</seg>
<seg id="630">If tenderers do not comply with this obligation, their tenders must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="631">In the Czech Republic, the contracting authority can decide whether to give the tenderer the opportunity to complete the missing documents.</seg>
<seg id="632">If the tenderer does not provide them, he must be expelled.</seg>
<seg id="633">In Germany, it is necessary to review not only the total price but also the unit prices.</seg>
<seg id="634">If the price structure of the tender shows that the prices for parts of the overall project have been estimated disproportionately high or low, tenderers must be asked for an explanation.</seg>
<seg id="635">If they do not provide explanations and if the contracting authority can prove that the tender contains compensatory prices, such tenders must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="636">This is to prevent bidders from submitting price calculations on the assumption that substantial quantitative changes will be made to individual parts of the overall project, which may lead to a significant increase in project costs.</seg>
<seg id="637">In the Czech Republic, the total price of the work is evaluated and the prices of individual parts are not examined in detail.</seg>
<seg id="638">Valuation compensation is not a reason to exclude a bid.</seg>
<seg id="639">In Germany, a contract cannot be awarded to a tenderer offering a disproportionately high or low price.</seg>
<seg id="640">If one or more tenders differ in price by 10% or more from the price estimated by the contracting authority or from other tenders, tenderers must prove that their tender has been credibly and convincingly calculated.</seg>
<seg id="641">If they are unable to do so, the contracting authority should exclude them.</seg>
<seg id="642">In the Czech Republic, the tender procedure may be canceled after a price review if only tenders with disproportionately low prices have been received and the tenderers have not substantiated these prices.</seg>
<seg id="643">If the price of the tender is significantly higher than the contracting authority's estimate, this is not a reason for refusing to award the contract to the tenderer concerned (unlike the German contracting law).</seg>
<seg id="644">If there is a suspicion in Germany of conduct intended to restrict competition, the contracting authority is obliged to report this fact immediately to the competent superior authority.</seg>
<seg id="645">He must decide on the further procedure and whether it is appropriate to inform the antitrust authority or law enforcement authorities.</seg>
<seg id="646">It must also approve (eg when the contract exceeds € 50,000 and the contract has not been awarded to the lowest bidder) whether the contract will be awarded when the contract is negotiated or whether the procurement procedure is canceled.</seg>
<seg id="647">Czech rules do not regulate this area.</seg>
<seg id="648">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Checking suitability and award criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined complied with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of some recommendations from potential suppliers made by self-employed persons, the contracting authorities did not check the suitability of the tenderers themselves.</seg>
<seg id="653">THIS segment IS intentionally LEFT blank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some procurement cases, insufficient documentation was provided as to whether the contracting authority took into account all published evaluation criteria or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested parties and confidentiality of tenders</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities used the services of unauthorized persons, such as self-employed persons or employees of building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were involved in the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions that were to be performed exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">The contracting authorities sought to substantiate this fact with their insufficient human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, self-employed professionals used the services of persons who were not formally bound to maintain the confidentiality of the offers and to exercise due diligence to fulfill their obligations under the contract.</seg>
<seg id="660">As far as contracting authorities are concerned, as a rule, there was no conclusive evidence as to whether tenders in the custody of self-employed professionals were available only to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Review and mathematical control of tenders</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting authorities handed over open envelopes for further verification to self-employed professionals without first carrying out the prescribed examination of tenders and mathematical examination and without documenting the results of these inspections.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intention to manipulate, third parties may have made changes to the tenders which could not be identified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="664">Examination of the documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in the tenders were not adequately identified or where price and product data were missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A sample check of one contracting authority revealed that in 75% of procurement cases, the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10% from the estimated costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One of the twenty tenders was canceled due to inadequate tender prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases, there was a lack of records or sufficient documentation on the examination of tenders or on negotiations with tenderers for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">In many cases, detailed information was also missing, eg on unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">Changes in market prices or increases in material costs were often cited as reasons for deviations.</seg>
<seg id="671">Contracting authorities have argued that it is difficult to identify and prove countervailing prices.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders made by an entity outside the scope of the normal contracting authorities, a 66% lower price was offered compared to the original cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="673">Data on a closer examination of costs or on the reasons for deviations were not recorded.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this issue, the contracting authority did not find any indication of price dumping for the tenderer to whom the contract might be awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clear whether the original cost estimate was excessive or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">Later, the contracting authority rated this bidder as a "low-cost company" that was unable to meet either the quality requirements or the deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a tenderer whose price was 35% higher than the original cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not cancel the tender procedure and put forward an unfounded argument that it could be assumed that the tenderer did not base its pricing on disproportionately high costs.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspected irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">Two cases of irregularities were found at one contracting authority, and these were reported to the company responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one tender procedure, two tenderers submitted tenders containing an identical price calculation, which led the contracting authority to exclude both tenders.</seg>
<seg id="682">The inspections did not reveal any significant deficiencies in the application of other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">SAO</seg>
<seg id="684">Verification of suitability</seg>
<seg id="685">For many construction projects, such as university buildings, roads and railways, contracting authorities did not exclude tenderers from participating in the tender procedure, even though they did not meet the contracting authority's requirements set out in the tender conditions or provided the required qualification or or explain the reason for the exclusion of the candidate who met the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Evaluation</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a wastewater treatment plant, the individual evaluation criteria of the tender procedure for the construction contractor were set, but the contracting authority did not respect them during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For the action in the field of railway infrastructure development, the weights of the evaluation criteria were not set at the beginning of the management when awarding the contract, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">For the road repair project, the assessment of the "shortening construction time" criterion was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For the second and third place tenderers, a greater reduction in construction time was incorrectly mentioned in the evaluation than was indicated in their tenders.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of the reasons for the selection of the candidate</seg>
<seg id="692">For three events related to housing support, the contracting authority did not document on the basis of which criteria it assessed the accepted offers and how it selected the most suitable one.</seg>
<seg id="693">The correctness of the selection of suppliers of small-scale contracts associated with the construction of the ring road with an estimated price of up to 500 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="694">CZK could not be verified, as the suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on the price and date of performance, but documents on these negotiations were not prepared.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for verifying and evaluating tenders comply with EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, they differ with regard to the specific management steps and the selection of individuals involved in the proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="698">In contrast to the Czech Republic, in Germany these steps in the procurement process are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross-principle and the protection of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, in some cases of inspections, it was found that the essential steps of the process in verifying and evaluating tenders were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The absence of control tools and transparency in decision-making during the examination and evaluation of tenders allows manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">The inspections revealed serious defects, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior proper verification and documentation of the tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of functions related to the examination and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased control of measures against increased possibilities for manipulation are necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">In all cases, the audited German contracting authorities did not use the complete set of available tools when checking the eligibility of prices and did not deal with their own price structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, shortcomings were found in the evaluation of the suitability of tenders and the use of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of the tender procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">After reviewing and evaluating the tenders, the procurement process is completed by awarding the contract or canceling the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the award decision.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request a review, if appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THIS segment IS intentionally LEFT blank</seg>
<seg id="712">The period of 10 days applies to electronic submission and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this period or before the decision of the review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and upholds the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the exercise of the award right reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by the swift implementation of procurement decisions.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority must duly document the course of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries have implemented management information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly performed verification and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract within the specified time.</seg>
<seg id="723">The reason is the fact that the tenderer is not bound by his tender after this deadline.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers should be informed of the result in good time, stating the reason why their tender has not been accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">Cancellation of the tender procedure is permissible only if certain conditions are met, eg if the prices in the tenders do not correspond to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting period of 10 or 15 days before concluding a contract applies to both European and national proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision only applies to European proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of a contract before a decision on its EU provision and a review has been made.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, the tender procedure must be canceled if a single tender has been received or only one tender has met the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that this tender meets the conditions set out in the tender dossier and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">The inspections found few inconsistencies in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases in European proceedings, companies authorizing letters were received before the expiry of the notification period, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also in several cases of open procedures, the letters of authority contained modifications incompatible with the content of the tender, such as new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting authorities did not meet the deadlines for the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because the tenderer offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to fulfill the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">During the reconstruction and construction of the university, in one case the contracting authority did not conclude a work contract with the contractor in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tender of the selected tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repairs, road construction, motorway and ring road projects, contracts were concluded later than required by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the case of construction modifications in former military districts, the contracting authority sent a notice of the selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers only after the expiry of the legal deadline.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the termination of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">Legal protection of unsuccessful candidates helps to reduce corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes the institute of legal protection even in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited time limit for concluding the contract was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can have adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting authorities should eliminate such shortcomings when closing a procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its various stages, relevant findings and decisions, including the relevant justifications, must be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">Completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">Data on procurement procedures are summarized in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document the procurement procedure is in line with the basic requirement of the principle of transparency, applied at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation on decision-making and justification guarantees transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to give detailed reasons for individual decisions and their justification significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In the case of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify their completion to the EU’s Office of Official Publications within 48 days of the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and thus fulfills the requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarize the essential details of its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics, which provide an overview of the development of the single market in construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed the provisions of the European Law on Documentation and Notification Obligations into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award of a contract applies not only to European procedures but also to national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those which are mandatory under European law, applies only to limited procedures exceeding the limit of 25 thousand. € (625 thousand CZK) and direct proceedings exceeding the limit of 15 thousand CZK € (375 thousand CZK) including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only participants in the proceedings are informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of assignments were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, such as the reasons for the supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In one case, the contracting authority did not explain why it had concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain the required particulars.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="780">In some European proceedings, the contracting authority erred in publishing the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several entries, there was no evidence of publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistically validated files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, the contract information was not disclosed due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the contracting authority half a year to notice the errors.</seg>
<seg id="788">As a result, the outcome of the proceedings was not disclosed during this period.</seg>
<seg id="789">SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organization of a major sporting event, significant deficiencies were found in the documentation on the course of the tender procedure, such as incorrect data on bid prices in the minutes of the evaluation committee meeting.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some documents on the opening of the envelopes were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="794">In the preparation of repairs and maintenance of roads, construction of the motorway and the ring road, the contract award notice was sent after the deadline or was not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">The Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to the German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The inspections revealed shortcomings that significantly reduced the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THIS segment IS intentionally LEFT blank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting authorities should further enhance the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits of the SAO and the BRH were focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">The aim of measures to prevent corruption is not only to avoid or at least reduce it, but also to prevent financial damage and possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The findings of the audit institutions of both audit institutions - the SAO and the BRH - with regard to the application of the procurement law of both countries and the comparison of its respective provisions give an internal view of common and different elements that may help both countries in further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">In both countries, there is thus an important common basis for public procurement and meeting the basic requirements of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting authorities reinforce these requirements in part with very extensive measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has applied the provisions on public procurement requiring European procedures to procedures that are below EU limits and are therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, inspections have shown that contracting authorities do not always fully comply with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate these inconsistencies, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, inspections identified risks affecting economy and value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">In particular, the incomplete definition of the subject of the public contract, which resulted in additional work that was often awarded in violation of the law, insufficient definition of the estimated price and the required qualifications to narrow the possible circle of bidders and thus reduce competition, especially in transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="816">Corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="817">The joint inspections were not aimed at detecting cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that the BRH and the SAO do not have sufficient tools for this.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can examine whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are being applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">Regarding corruption prevention, the two countries focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, the German provisions leave room for wide and unrestricted competition, transparency and controls as a central element in preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">Czech regulations primarily aim at strengthening the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles for the prevention of corruption, which apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been incorporated into public procurement requirements and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes even very precisely, the ways in which the requirements for the prevention of corruption during the procurement procedure and for the selection of persons included in it are met.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the opinion of the BRH, the principle of preference for open tenders and calls for participation is a particularly suitable tool for significantly reducing the risk of corruption in public procurement, while restricting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate control (especially the principle of cross-checking), transparency requirements, tender documentation and various organizational measures are also effective mechanisms for preventing corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">Therefore, BRH does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions, which public institutions must comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas highlighted weaknesses in complying with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting authorities should provide their employees with further training to familiarize them with anti-corruption requirements and further increase their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the identified weaknesses relates to activities that the construction administration has delegated to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls in the delegation of powers increases the risk of their abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities prone to manipulation and corruption should therefore be outsourced to third parties only if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorized interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">In the Czech Republic, anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at the governmental level, which also significantly affect the area of ​​public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO's audits took place at a time when one of the most important parts of this strategy had been implemented, namely a significant amendment to the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of related implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The adopted strategy and new legislation can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">Under the new regulations, for example, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the public contract, the determination of the estimated value of the public contract, the adequacy of qualification requirements, the determination of basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendation</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both the SAO and the BRH have a favorable opinion on how to implement EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their widespread application in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements for competition, equal treatment and transparency form an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The transnational model introduced in the EU can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential of material and intangible damages resulting from manipulation and corruption in connection with the award of public contracts, the BRH and the SAO insist that it is the duty of contracting authorities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and improve them where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organizational structures and processes of procurement procedures should be continuously monitored for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for corrective action and to respond appropriately.</seg>
<seg id="847">In comparison with the practice in Germany, it turned out that the share of open tenders in the Czech Republic should increase, which gives room to competition and significantly reduces the possibility of corrupt behavior.</seg>
<seg id="848">Partial procurement can also have a positive impact on the price achieved, where this is permissible and appropriate for the contracting authority. A higher number of bidders puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring its organization also has an impact on the course of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is provided by special state organizations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport constructions, it is organized by central authorities themselves or through contracted organizations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and the BRH wish to further develop knowledge in their work where appropriate, and to address it with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">In addition, they are convinced that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance for effectively combating corruption and guaranteeing that public contracts are awarded in a well-functioning and fair competition regime and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Side dishes</seg>
</p>
