<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="online-B">
<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT on the results of parallel inspections of the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint final report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">The Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="7">The presented joint report informs about the course and result of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on the administration of excise duties in 2012–2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between the supreme audit institutions of both countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO SR and the SAO CR in the performance of parallel controls focused on the administration of excise duties, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel controls was chosen on the basis of the fact that both EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to find out how it is applied at the national level, how the excise administration system is set up and how the systems in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are different.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the inspections carried out was the exchange of experiences, the identification of differences and the identification of good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, the benefit was that the international comparability of data on the efficiency and effectiveness of excise administration is very limited without the implementation of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrík,</seg>
<seg id="14">president</seg>
<seg id="15">chairman</seg>
<seg id="16">Of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel inspections of the SPD administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legal regulation of excise duties in the Czech Republic and in the Slovak Republic and their administration is in accordance with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences were found between the adjustment of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic; in the Czech Republic, verification of the economic stability of applicants for permits and mandatory marking and coloring of selected mineral oils and some other oils contributes to the effective administration of excise duties; In the Slovak Republic, the distribution of control stamps is simpler than in the Czech Republic and is less burdensome for the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against excise tax evasion, the supervision of the movement of raw tobacco, resp. tobacco raw materials, implementation of the institute of fuel distributor and registration of sellers of consumer packaging of alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="23">Revenues from excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's goals of reducing labor taxation, introducing eco-saving measures and reducing tobacco and alcohol dependence have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, partly because excise tax rate indexation has not been introduced in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This results in a reduction in the importance of excise duties on total tax revenues and, as a result of growing purchasing power, a real reduction in the tax burden on excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="26">The introduction of environmental measures has been financially supported by the state for a long time, but these measures have a negative impact on excise tax revenues, which will have to be replaced in the future by other revenues or reductions in state expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditures on the administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic have been growing for a long time, mainly due to wage growth, and their efficiency is declining.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the Slovak Republic, this efficiency is also negatively affected by expenditures on the electronic administration of excise duties (IT expenditures) and expenditures on wages of employees performing permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses for alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="29">The electronic administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic did not have a significant effect on reducing the number of tax administrators.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO CR and the SAO SR recommend the FR SR to reconsider the justification for the performance of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses for alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the efficiency of administrative expenditures was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures in the audited period that would lead to a reduction in the personnel intensity of the excise tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative acts of tax administrators in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in individual years of the audited period was similar, while the number of comparable tax entities in the Slovak Republic is about a third lower than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic perform administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical performance of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic is more administratively demanding than in the Czech Republic and, due to the ratio of the number of tax acts to the number of entities, also more expensive.</seg>
<seg id="35">The electronic administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
