<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel control of the value added tax administration carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">The 1977 Lima Declaration emphasizes that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) have the power to audit all public financial transactions.</seg>
<seg id="4">The declaration calls for tax revenues to be controlled as much as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The European Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers the tax to be one of the most important components of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">VI. The EUROSAI Congress, held in Bonn in 2005, dealt with the audit of public revenues carried out by the SAI.</seg>
<seg id="7">An important step on the way to optimizing the SAI's control activities is the development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenues.</seg>
<seg id="8">This concerns in particular taxes as the largest source of public revenue, which is most prone to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAIs may to some extent be unable to carry out control activities without the cooperation of another state's SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organized fraud, which causes significant revenue losses in many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In order to combat this crime, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">SAIs that carry out inspections in this area must be willing to work more closely together.</seg>
<seg id="13">Right on VI. The EUROSAI Congress in Bonn gave rise to the idea of ​​carrying out an audit of the value added tax ('VAT') administration and the VIES system in cooperation with the Supreme Audit Office and the Federal Court of Auditors, the Bundesrechnungshof.</seg>
<seg id="14">Careful preparation followed, when both parties first had to get acquainted with the legal environment and procedures for VAT administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the analysis of this information, a selection of control topics was made, which were included in the control program.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving efficient and effective VAT administration is a long-term challenge and individual states (especially the Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve, simplify and make the collection of this tax more transparent.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrations, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the system of international information exchange.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the value added tax administration carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Inspection number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Administration of value added tax after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Verification of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Objective of the inspection:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of financial authorities in the administration of value added tax after the Czech Republic's integration into the single internal market of the European Union ("EU") associated with the free movement of goods and services and to verify the use of VIES, in particular when monitoring the exercise of the right to exemption from value added tax in intra-Community supplies.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The purpose of the audit was to examine the system of control of intra-Community value added tax with a special focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the above-mentioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on the weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">Value Added Information Exchange System The inspections were carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter "SAO") and the German Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter "BRH") in mutual cooperation on the basis of an agreement concluded between the two auditing institutions on 8 June 2006. .</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the examination of selected business transactions carried out between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter "CR") and the Federal Republic of Germany ("Germany"), the use of information obtained through international cooperation between tax administrations and comparison of VAT administration systems of both countries. .</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of audits was prepared in accordance with European Directive No. 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period was the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel control in the area of ​​VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was performed on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the main point - the exchange of information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004 - the audit covered other topics, such as taxpayer registration, VAT returns and recapitulative statements, which are closely connected with the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the audit included the legal situation in the field of international bus and coach transport and the comparison of some statistics.</seg>
<seg id="36">A comparison of the VAT administration systems of the two countries revealed differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion (among others) for registration is exceeding the limit set in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, taxpayers are assigned only one tax identification number, which they also use in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, taxpayers are assigned a tax number when registering for VAT, serving only for business transactions in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If a German taxpayer intends to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different ways of registration cause problems, conditions should be balanced across the EU (see 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus passenger transport.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international bus transport of passengers is exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, part of the transport that takes place on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">Efforts should be made at EU level to harmonize the situation within the meaning of Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of VAT (see 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="47">3) Tax returns for VAT.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic taxpayers file VAT returns only for individual tax periods (month or quarter), in Germany taxpayers are obliged to file so-called preliminary VAT returns (monthly or quarterly) and after the end of the calendar year they must file an annual VAT return. .</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike in the Czech Republic, taxpayers in Germany are obliged to file preliminary tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of the obligation to file VAT returns in the Czech Republic electronically would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">4) Summary reports.</seg>
