<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the Results of International Cooperation in Excise Tax Administration Controls between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">The presented joint report informs about the course and result of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, focused on the administration of excise duties in the period after both countries join the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The co - operation was carried out on the basis of an agreement on co - operation in control activities, concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel controls was chosen with regard to the fundamental change in the system of collection of excise duties, which occurred in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union on 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the European Union's internal market requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of tax-free goods until the day of their delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows for the movement of goods under fiscal supervision under a duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on tax administrations and presupposes close cooperation between the competent administrative authorities of the Member States in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in controls on the administration of excise duties for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Inspection number: (CZ) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of control: (Czech Republic) Administration of excise duties (Slovak Republic) Procedure of customs authorities in the administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="14">On 8 February 2006, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SAO-CR”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SAO SR”) concluded an “Agreement on Cooperation in Audit Activities”.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the agreement was cooperation in parallel inspections "Excise Tax Administration", included in the SAO-CR inspection plan for 2005 under No. 05/34, and "Control of the procedure of customs authorities in excise administration", included in the SAO inspection plan SR for the year 2006 under No. 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel inspections were in the nature of coordinated inspections.</seg>
<seg id="17">The co-operation consisted in exchanging information which the contracting parties could not obtain during the control of excise administration in their territory and in preparing a joint final report on the result of controls in accordance with European implementing directives for the implementation of INTOSAI auditing standards - Directive 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the territory of the Czech Republic, inspections (hereinafter referred to as the “Czech Republic”) were carried out by groups of inspectors from the state budget department and territorial departments of Central Bohemia, Southern Bohemia, Western Bohemia, Northwestern Bohemia, Northeastern Bohemia, Southern Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia. February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="20">The auditees were the General Directorate of Customs ("GDC") and 11 tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the GDC, 12 selected customs offices out of the total number of 54 were inspected.</seg>
<seg id="22">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the “SR”) was carried out by the Finance and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice branches at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 in the period from 13 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">8 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel controls was to examine the customs authorities' practice in administering excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation focused on the procedure of tax administrators in supervising the transport of excisable goods, especially on the registration of started and terminated transport in the regime of conditional tax exemption, and on the exchange of information within mutual administrative assistance between excise tax administrators of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="27">Until 31 December 2003, the administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic was performed by financial authorities.</seg>
<seg id="28">From 1 January 2004, this agenda was taken over by the customs authorities, which until now collected excise duty only on imports.</seg>
<seg id="29">Mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products are subject to excise duty in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="30">The state budget revenue from excise duties in the Czech Republic totaled CZK 82.8 billion in 2004, and excise duties accounted for 19.5% of state budget revenue from taxes and fees of CZK 424.7 billion.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, state budget revenues from excise duties amounted to CZK 103.6 billion and the share of state budget revenues from taxes and fees in the amount of CZK 460.4 billion was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the revenue from the excise duty on mineral oils to the state budget amounted to 80% of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 it was 90.9%.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference compared to 100% of CZK 13 billion in 2004 and CZK 6.9 billion in 2005 was the revenue of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of all excise duties in the Slovak Republic has been performed by the customs authorities since 1 May 2004, with the exception of the excise duty on mineral oil, which they have been administering since 1 January 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, the administration of excise duties was carried out by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="36">Mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products are subject to excise duty in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">The state budget revenue from excise duties in the Slovak Republic in 2004 totaled Sk 43.4 billion, and excise duties accounted for 20.7% of total tax revenues of Sk 209.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, state budget revenue from excise duties was Sk 50 billion, and excise duties accounted for 22.5% of total tax revenues of Sk 222.6 billion.</seg>
<seg id="39">Graph No. 1 - Comparison of revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic from taxes and fees and tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic with revenues from excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="40">Legislation in both countries is based on European Union legislation in this area, in particular: - Council Directive 92/12 / EEC on the general arrangements for products subject to excise duty and on the holding, movement and monitoring of such products (hereinafter "Directive 92/12 / EEC") ), - Council Regulation (EC) No 2073/2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as 'Regulation No 2073/2004'), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 2719/92 on the official accompanying document for shipments - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 3649/92 on the simplified accompanying document for the movement of excise goods which have been subject to excise duty suspension released for home use in the Member State of dispatch within the Community ('Regulation No 3649/92').</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legal regulation regulating the issue of excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No. 353/2003 Coll., On excise duties, as amended, (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 353/2003 Coll.”), Effective from 1 January 2004.</seg>
<seg id="42">When administering excise duties in the Slovak Republic, the customs authorities are bound, inter alia, by the following generally binding legal regulations: - Act No. 98/2004 Coll., On excise duty on mineral oil, as amended (hereinafter “Act No. 98/2004 Coll. Act No. 104/2004 Coll., on excise duty on wine, as amended (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 104/2004 Coll.”), - Act No. 105/2004 On excise duty on alcohol, as amended (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 105/2004 Coll.”), - Act No. 106/2004 Coll., On excise duty on tobacco products, as amended regulations (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 106/2004 Coll.”), - Act No. 107/2004 Coll., on excise duty on beer, as amended (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 107/2004 Coll. of.").</seg>
<seg id="43">2.1 Movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty between the Member States of the European Union</seg>
<seg id="44">The conditions for the movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty are laid down in Directive 92/12 / EEC in Title III - Movement of goods, Articles 15 to 20.</seg>
<seg id="45">Under those provisions, the transport of those goods may be carried out only by an authorized warehousekeeper, which is a natural or legal person authorized by the competent authorities of a Member State to manufacture, process, store, receive and dispatch excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="46">The consignee in another Member State may be an authorized warehousekeeper or an economic operator without the status of authorized warehousekeeper, who, however, may not store or re-dispatch these products under the duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="47">Authorized warehousekeeper in the Czech Republic and in the Slovak Republic means the operator of a tax warehouse, the economic entity is the authorized consignee for repeated or one-time acceptance of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Directive 92/12 / EEC, the movement of products subject to excise duty under suspension of excise duty is possible only with an accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="49">The consignment note shall be issued by the consignor in four copies before the start of the shipment, unless another copy is requested by the competent authorities of the Member State of dispatch.</seg>
<seg id="50">2.2 Procedure for starting and ending the transport of goods in the regime of conditional tax exemption between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="51">Transport from the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="52">The procedure for starting transport is regulated by the provisions of Section 25, Paragraph 3 of Act No. 353/2003 Coll., Which states, inter alia:</seg>
<seg id="53">'Before the transport of selected products begins, the operator of the tax warehouse shall inform the customs office which is locally competent for the tax warehouse from which the transport is to commence;</seg>
<seg id="54">the transport of selected products can only be started with the consent of this customs office.</seg>
<seg id="55">The customs office shall give its consent to the transport of the selected products immediately after the condition of securing the tax is met ... '</seg>
<seg id="56">The consignor in the Czech Republic may start the transport of all types of products subject to excise duty only with the consent of the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="57">The customs office shall give its consent to the commencement of transport only if a tax security is provided in the amount of the tax due on the transported products.</seg>
<seg id="58">The consignor is obliged to prepare an accompanying document in five copies before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="59">The customs office shall indicate on the accompanying document the consent to the commencement of transport.</seg>
<seg id="60">Copy No 1 shall be kept by the consignor, copies No 2, 3 and 4 shall be handed over by the consignor to the carrier and copy No 5 shall be kept by the customs office authorizing the transport.</seg>
<seg id="61">According to Slovak legislation, the recipient will keep copy No. 2 of the accompanying document in the Slovak Republic. On copies No. 3 and 4, he shall confirm the receipt of the products and submit both copies to the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="62">Copy No 3, certified by the customs office, shall be sent to the consignor no later than the 15th day of the month following the calendar month in which he received the products.</seg>
<seg id="63">Copy No 4 shall be kept by the customs office of the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="64">The transport is terminated by the acceptance of the products by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="65">The customs office in the Czech Republic that authorized the commencement of the transport shall decide on the release of the tax security within 5 working days after the submission of copy No. 3 of the accompanying document, which is confirmed by the consignee and the Slovak customs office.</seg>
<seg id="66">Graph No. 2 - Circulation of the accompanying document during transport started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="67">Transport from Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="68">Until 31 December 2005, the procedure for the transport of alcohol and tobacco products from the Slovak Republic to another Member State of the European Union was amended as follows:</seg>
<seg id="69">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 26, Paragraph 4 of Act No. 105/2004 Coll.</seg>
<seg id="70">'When transporting alcohol from a tax warehouse in a tax territory to a tax warehouse or to an authorized consignee or to a tax agent in another Member State, the consignor (supplier) shall send a copy of the first part of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the Poprad Customs Office on the day the transport begins; he shall also send this copy to the customs office in writing within five working days from the date of commencement of the shipment. "</seg>
<seg id="71">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 22, Paragraph 4 of Act No. 106/2004 Coll.</seg>
<seg id="72">'When transporting tobacco products from a tax warehouse in a tax territory to a tax warehouse or to an authorized consignee or tax agent in another Member State, the consignor ’(supplier’) shall send a copy of the first part of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the Poprad Customs Office on the day the transport begins; he shall also send this copy to the customs office in writing no later than five working days from the date of commencement of the shipment. "</seg>
<seg id="73">When transporting other products subject to excise duty (mineral oil, wine and beer) in the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 (hereinafter referred to as the “audited period”), the tax entity was not obliged to notify the Poprad Customs Office, resp. the competent customs office of departure under the duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="74">The tax administrator learned about the transport of these products only during a local investigation or tax inspection from the accompanying documents and from the accounting documents of the tax subject.</seg>
<seg id="75">Before starting the transport, the consignor in the Slovak Republic is obliged to prepare an accompanying document in four copies.</seg>
<seg id="76">Copy No. 1 shall be kept by the consignor (when transporting alcohol and tobacco products, he shall send a copy of copy No. 1 electronically or by fax to the Poprad Customs Office and the relevant customs office).</seg>
<seg id="77">Copies No. 2, 3 and 4 accompany the transported goods.</seg>
<seg id="78">According to the Czech legislation, the recipient in the Czech Republic will keep copy No. 2 of the accompanying document issued by the sender in the Slovak Republic and will confirm the receipt of the products on copies No. 3 and 4.</seg>
<seg id="79">Confirmed copies No. 3 and 4 shall be sent to the locally competent customs office in the Czech Republic no later than the first working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="80">The customs office shall retain copy No 4 and return copy No 3, on which it shall verify correctness and validity, to the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="81">The consignee shall send the certified copy No. 3 no later than the next working day after its receipt to the sender to the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="82">Transport in the Slovak Republic is considered to be completed on the day of receipt of the products by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="83">The sender proves the termination of the transport by submitting copy No. 3 of the accompanying document confirmed by the consignee and the tax administrator in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="84">Graph No. 3 - Circulation of the accompanying document during transport (alcohol and tobacco products) started in the Slovak Republic and ended in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="85">In 2006, amendments to all laws on excise duties were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under conditional tax exemption is obliged to send a copy of copy No. 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the locally competent consignor before commencing transport.</seg>
<seg id="86">The document proving the termination of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products is copy No. 3 of the accompanying document confirmed by the recipient and his relevant tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="87">The document proving the termination of the transport of mineral oils, wine and beer is copy No. 3 confirmed by the recipient.</seg>
<seg id="88">The confirmation of the tax administrator of another Member State of the receipt of the said goods by the consignee is required if this administrator is obliged under the legislation of the Member State concerned to certify copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="89">2.3 Records of started and terminated transports kept by customs authorities in the Czech Republic and in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="90">There is no single electronic system for monitoring the movement of goods under the duty suspension arrangement between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="91">Decision 1152/2003 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 on computerising the movement and surveillance of excisable products requires Member States and the European Commission to set up an electronic Excise Movement and Control System from 1 July 2009. ), which would allow excise administrators in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the movement of goods.</seg>
<seg id="92">The system will allow the electronic transmission of accompanying documents, which are currently used only in paper form, and will help to facilitate the movement of goods under suspension of excise duty and ensure more effective control of the movement of tax-free products within all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="93">This system will include the national transport databases of the individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="94">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic registers all transports started and terminated on the territory of the Czech Republic in the module of Records of Selected Products (hereinafter referred to as "EVV").</seg>
<seg id="95">All customs authorities in the Czech Republic have online access to the system.</seg>
<seg id="96">In the case of transport carried out only on the territory of the Czech Republic, the tax administrator may obtain information on the commencement or termination of the transport immediately after the registration of the accompanying document by the customs office in the EVV.</seg>
<seg id="97">The customs office shall release the tax security for the transported products provided by the consignor at the moment of registration of the termination of the transport by the customs office to the locally competent consignee.</seg>
<seg id="98">Customs offices in the Slovak Republic use a database based on the SysNed application software, which ensures the automation of their activities in the administration of excise duties and communication with European Union systems.</seg>
<seg id="99">By registering the tax warehouse, the tax warehouse operator or the authorized recipient in the SysNed application software, this data is automatically transferred to the "System for Exchange of Excise Data" database (hereinafter referred to as "SEED").</seg>
<seg id="100">3. Preparation and course of cooperation</seg>
<seg id="101">The first coordination meeting of the SAO-CR representatives and the SAO SR representatives, at which a specific procedure of cooperation in the implementation of parallel controls in the field of excise duties was discussed, took place in January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="102">Both parties became acquainted with the legislation in the field of excise duties and with the organization of the administration of excise duties in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="103">Special attention was paid to the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the authorization, respectively. when initiating and terminating the movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty and the exchange of information between the excise administrators of the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">At the meeting, it was agreed that the Czech and Slovak sides: - process overall data on the amount of excise goods transported from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic and vice versa, whose transport began in the audited period, - compare data on mineral oil shipments - Combined Nomenclature code 2710 and 2711 and alcohol - code of the combined nomenclature 2207 and 2208 in the regime of conditional exemption from tax started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic and vice versa in the months of November 2004 and September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="105">During the inspections, the audited periods were extended to October and November 2005, and in these months the transport of tobacco products under the conditional tax exemption regime was also subject to the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="106">Tables No. 1 and No. 2 show the total quantity of products subject to excise duty that were transported under the conditional tax exemption regime between Czech and Slovak tax entities in the audited period.</seg>
<seg id="107">4. Comparison of records of transport of goods in the regime of conditional exemption from tax</seg>
<seg id="108">The SAO-CR handed over to the Slovak side a database of transports terminated in the Czech Republic, which contained a total of 5,876 items listed on the accompanying documents, of which 5,738 items related to mineral oils, 134 items to alcohol and 4 items to tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="109">The SAO SR handed over to the Czech side a database of transports terminated in the Slovak Republic, which contained a total of 3,319 items listed on the accompanying documents, of which 696 items related to mineral oil, 2,066 items of alcohol and 557 items of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="110">The SAO-CR compared data on transports listed in the register of started transports in the Czech Republic with data on completed transports registered in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="111">The results of the comparison are shown in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="112">Data on transports in November 2004 and September 2005 were compared by the SAO-CR with the database of the Slovak customs administration, which was handed over to it by the SAO SR at the beginning of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="113">The database did not contain data enabling reliable reconciliation of individual transports, and therefore only 63% of started transports were managed to be assigned.</seg>
<seg id="114">Individual shipments were assigned according to multiple data, eg shipper, consignee, date of shipment, quantity of transported products.</seg>
<seg id="115">Data on transports started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic in October and November 2005 were compared by the SAO-CR with the database of the Slovak customs administration, which contained all data according to accompanying documents, on the basis of which 93% of started transports were clearly assigned.</seg>
<seg id="116">In the database of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, data on the amount of mineral oils were given in liters or tonnes, depending on the type of mineral oil.</seg>
<seg id="117">The quantity of alcohol was in most cases given in liters, which could, however, be converted into liters of absolute alcohol on the basis of the percentage alcohol content indicated in the database.</seg>
<seg id="118">The quantity of tobacco products was stated in pieces, in thousands and in kilograms according to the type of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="119">For transports started in the Czech Republic, the completion of which could not be reliably verified in the Slovak database or for which the data on the transported quantity of products did not match, the accompanying documents were checked.</seg>
<seg id="120">Accompanying documents for 487 shipments of alcohol, mineral oils and tobacco products were inspected.</seg>
<seg id="121">The inspection of these documents was carried out at the customs offices at which the SAO-CR performed the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="122">For transport authorized by other customs offices, the accompanying documents were requested through the GDC.</seg>
<seg id="123">The Czech side requested the Slovak side to verify the implementation of 141 shipments for which the customs authorities in the Czech Republic did not provide certified copies No. 3 of the accompanying document, or the quantity of products stated on the accompanying document did not agree with the quantity of products listed in the database.</seg>
<seg id="124">Furthermore, the Slovak side was provided with data on transports registered in the Slovak database, which, however, did not contain the transport database of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="125">The SAO SR searched for 95 transports in the database of the Slovak Customs Administration.</seg>
<seg id="126">The verification of the remaining 46 shipments was requested by the locally competent customs offices, which proved their completion with copies of the accompanying documents.</seg>
<seg id="127">The Slovak side forwarded to the Czech side copies of the accompanying documents, on the basis of which the transports were also identified in the Czech database, with the exception of transports performed by two Czech tax entities, which were not found in the Czech database of started transports.</seg>
<seg id="128">The inspection of these cases revealed:</seg>
<seg id="129">- in the Slovak transport database, 11 transports of alcohol in the total amount of 276.7 liters of alcohol realized by the Czech tax entity in 2004 and 20 transports of alcohol in the total amount of 404.66 liters of alcohol realized in 2005 were registered.</seg>
<seg id="130">The SAO-CR found that these were transports of taxed products for the initiation of which the sender does not need the consent of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="131">The sender informed the tax administrator in writing about the start of the transport. He carried out the transport on the basis of accompanying documents, which are used for the transport of products under the conditional tax exemption regime;</seg>
<seg id="132">- in the Slovak transport database, a total of 94 transports of mineral oils were registered, combined nomenclature code 2710 11 21, in the total volume of 173 thous. liters realized by the Czech tax entity in the period from September 2004 to December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="133">The SAO-CR found that in the period from May 2004 to June 2005, the tax subject carried out a transport of 102 thous. liters of untaxed mineral oils without proper authorization.</seg>
<seg id="134">The taxable person held a special permit for the receipt and use of exempt products, on the basis of which he could supply non-taxed products only to the holder of the same permit.</seg>
<seg id="135">He did not notify the customs office in the Czech Republic of the commencement of transport and did not provide tax security in the amount of CZK 1,207,680 for the transported products.</seg>
<seg id="136">In the period from July 2005 to December 2005, the tax subject transported 71 thous. liters of taxed mineral oils. Even in these cases, he failed to fulfill his legal obligation by notifying the customs office of the commencement of transport.</seg>
<seg id="137">The consignor in the Czech Republic may start the transport of products released for free circulation in the tax territory of the Czech Republic to another Member State without the consent of the customs office, but he is obliged to notify the customs office of this fact in writing before commencing transport.</seg>
<seg id="138">A taxable person taking products released for free circulation in another Member State is obliged to declare the quantity and secure the tax before taking it.</seg>
<seg id="139">Products may be transported only with a simplified accompanying document, the details of which are regulated by Regulation No 3649/92.</seg>
<seg id="140">This Regulation also allows the use of an accompanying document for transport under a duty suspension arrangement, which must, however, clearly indicate that it is a "simplified accompanying document for tax control purposes (products subject to excise duty)".</seg>
<seg id="141">The same legal regulation of transport and acceptance of products released for free tax circulation in another Member State also applies in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="142">In the above cases, the tax subjects transported the products released for free tax circulation with an accompanying document for transport in the regime of conditional exemption from tax, the 3rd and 4th copies of which the recipient submitted to the tax administrator in the Slovak Republic for verification.</seg>
<seg id="143">The customs authorities in the Slovak Republic registered these transports in the database of transports in the regime of conditional exemption from tax, as it was not stated on the accompanying documents that it was a simplified accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="144">The SAO SR compared the transport database of the Czech customs administration with the transport database of the Slovak customs administration and found out:</seg>
<seg id="145">- in the databases, the quantity of transported products was stated inconsistently, eg mineral oil was stated in liters, hectoliters or kilograms; the alcohol was expressed in liters or liters of alcohol, making it difficult to compare the quantities of goods transported,</seg>
<seg id="146">- the quantity of alcohol transported indicated on the invoices did not correspond to the quantity recorded in the databases,</seg>
<seg id="147">- the databases did not list all the related invoices,</seg>
<seg id="148">- in the database of the Slovak customs administration, two shipments of alcohol from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic were registered in November 2004 in the total volume of 47,237 liters of alcohol, which were not in the database of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Slovak side submitted copies of accompanying documents to the Czech side.</seg>
<seg id="150">5. International exchange of information between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="151">Until 30 June 2005, the conditions for cooperation between the administrations of the Member States responsible for administering excise duties were governed by Council Directive 77/799 / EEC on mutual assistance between the competent authorities of the Member States in the field of direct taxation, certain excise duties and taxes on insurance premiums.</seg>
<seg id="152">On 1 July 2005, Regulation No 2073/2004 entered into force, which lays down rules and procedures enabling the competent authorities of the Member States of the European Union to cooperate and exchange the information necessary for the correct assessment of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="153">Each Member State shall designate a central liaison office to liaise with the other Member States in the field of excise administration and to be responsible for exchanging information on the movement of excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="154">In the Czech Republic, the "Excise Liaison Office" (hereinafter referred to as the "ELO CR") was established at the GDC to ensure the exchange of information in the field of excise duties between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="155">With effect from 1 May 2004, the ELO Office at the Poprad Customs Office provided tasks related to the administration of systems for controlling the movement of excisable goods (SEED, MVS, EWSE) and the exchange of information within mutual administrative assistance between the Member States of the European Union and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">With effect from 1 July 2005, the tasks of the ELO Office are performed by the ELO Department (based in Poprad) of the Excise Tax Department of the Customs Directorate of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "ELO SR").</seg>
<seg id="157">Pursuant to Article 3 (3) of Regulation No 2073/2004, the central liaison office is responsible in particular for: - the exchange of data held in the SEED electronic register, - the 'Early Warning System Excise' (EWSE), - requests for verification movement of excise goods sent to or received from other Member States by the "Movement Verification System" (hereinafter referred to as "MSS").</seg>
<seg id="158">The content, scope and functions of the SEED, EWSE and MVS systems are regulated in Articles 22, 23 and 24 of Regulation 2073/2004.</seg>
<seg id="159">SEED - a system for the exchange of information on taxable persons trading in excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="160">The system is made up of national registers of excise duty payers and allows tax administrations in the European Union to find out whether products subject to excise duty are traded by an authorized person.</seg>
<seg id="161">Each national register shall be made available to the competent authorities of the other Member States for excise purposes only.</seg>
<seg id="162">The central liaison office of each Member State shall ensure that persons involved in the movement of excise goods within the territory of the European Union can obtain confirmation of the information held in this database.</seg>
<seg id="163">In accordance with Section 41 of Act No. 98/2004 Coll., With Section 39 of Act No. 104/2004 Coll., With Section 46 of Act No. 105/2004 Coll., With Section 40 of Act No. 106/2004 Coll., Section 39 of Act No. 107/2004 Coll., ELO SR maintains an electronic database containing a register of operators of tax warehouses, authorized recipients and tax warehouses - the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="164">Customs offices in the Slovak Republic contribute to the SEED database by registering a tax warehouse, a tax warehouse operator or an authorized consignee in the SysNed application software, which is automatically connected to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="165">For example, if a new tax warehouse operator, authorized beneficiary or tax warehouse is registered in the SysNed database, the related data is automatically transferred to the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="166">The SAO SR found that the exchange of SEED databases between the Customs Administration of the SR and the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic took place in the audited period usually once a month, exceptionally several times a month.</seg>
<seg id="167">The Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic received 22 SEED files and sent 25 SEED files.</seg>
<seg id="168">The data are transferred to the SEED database in the Czech Republic from the national register, in which all persons authorized to dispose of products subject to excise duty and issued authorizations to dispose of these products are registered.</seg>
<seg id="169">Individual customs offices in the Czech Republic do not have access to the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="170">Requests from customs offices for the provision of information from the SEED database of other member countries are obtained only through the ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="171">EWSE - an early warning system aimed at controlling the transport of excisable goods, through which the transport of risky consignments is notified.</seg>
<seg id="172">The transport of certain products subject to excise duty in quantities exceeding the limits set by a regulation of the European Commission and the transport assessed as risky by the tax administrator are considered risky consignments.</seg>
<seg id="173">The exchange of information is realized in two forms:</seg>
<seg id="174">- information - sent when the set limits are exceeded,</seg>
<seg id="175">- warning message - sent if the transport of goods is assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="176">When evaluating the degree of risk of a consignment, ELO SR uses the SEED database to send a warning message, on the basis of which it checks the data stated in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the event that the data in the SEED database do not match the data in the accompanying document (for example, the registration number of the consignee does not match or the consignee's registered office), ELO SR will prepare a warning message to send to the ELO.</seg>
<seg id="178">When drawing up the reports, ELO follows the regulations of the Commission for Taxation and Customs, CED 317 and CED 457, which determine, inter alia, the type and quantity of goods in the relevant units of measurement for drawing up information and warning reports.</seg>
<seg id="179">During the audited period, ELO SR sent one warning message to ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information on started shipments of products in quantities exceeding the set limits is generated automatically when entering data from the accompanying document into the database when approving the shipment.</seg>
<seg id="181">If the tax administrator in the Czech Republic evaluates the consignment as risky on the basis of its own analysis, it will prepare a so-called warning message, which it will send to the relevant Member State via the ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005, ELO CR sent two warning messages to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">MVS - the system of control of the movement of goods - enables, through MVS applications, to control individual shipments of products subject to excise duty as well as control of the determined route of transport between the entities listed in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information takes place on the basis of a request in which the ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system is used mainly in cases where the sender receives a certified copy No. 3 of the accompanying document and requests, for example, a refund of excise duty, and in cases where the data contained in the accompanying document cannot be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="186">In the audited period, ELO SR sent 33 requests to the ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="187">ELO CR sent ELO SR 25 MVS applications.</seg>
<seg id="188">The customs offices in the Czech Republic most often checked the data stated in the accompanying documents, especially the amount received, resp. of the products dispatched or whether the consignor of the products listed in the accompanying document is authorized to handle the excise goods, if this could not be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="189">In both countries, the applications received by the RAC were forwarded to the customs offices locally responsible for the consignee or consignor of the excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="190">The customs authorities checked the required data and communicated the result of the investigation to the other Member State via ELO.</seg>
<seg id="191">6. Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">The cooperation between the SAO-CR and the SAO SR made it possible to compare the basic legal regulations governing excise duties in both countries, the procedure of the Czech and Slovak customs authorities to start and stop the transport of products under conditional tax exemption between the two countries, records of these transports and between customs authorities in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 A comparison of legal regulations governing the area of ​​excise duties in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic revealed differences:</seg>
<seg id="194">(a) in the procedure of taxable persons and tax administrations when initiating the transport of products under a duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="195">The tax subject in the Czech Republic may start the transport of products under the conditional tax exemption regime only with the consent of the tax administrator, who will allow the start of transport provided that the transported products have been provided with a tax security in the amount of tax due to them.</seg>
<seg id="196">The commencement of the transport of products under the conditional tax exemption regime in the Slovak Republic is not subject to the permission of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="197">During the audited period, the tax entity was obliged to notify the tax administrator of the commencement of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">He could start transporting mineral oils, beer and wine without informing the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, amendments to all laws on excise duties were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under conditional tax exemption is obliged to send a copy of copy No. 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office locally competent for the consignor;</seg>
<seg id="200">(b) within the time limits for sending copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The consignee in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copy No. 3 and 4 of the accompanying document to the tax administrator for verification no later than the next working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">He is obliged to send the certified copy No. 3 to the sender no later than the next working day after receiving it from the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in the Slovak Republic is obliged to send the sender of the products a copy No. 3 confirmed by the tax administrator and the consignee of the products no later than the 15th day of the month following the month in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">6.2. Customs authorities in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of transports of products in the regime of conditional tax exemption.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and manner of keeping these records is not regulated by law in the Czech Republic or in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="206">The customs authorities in both countries enter in the register all data from the accompanying documents on the basis of which the transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">There is currently no single electronic system for monitoring the movement of goods under suspension of excise duty between the Member States of the European Union, which would allow excise administrators in the individual Member States to obtain information on the movement of goods in real time.</seg>
<seg id="208">Decision 1152/2003 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 provides for the introduction of an electronic system for monitoring the movement of excisable products from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">Based on the agreement on cooperation in control activities, the Czech side handed over to the Slovak side a database of transports of products under the conditional tax exemption regime initiated in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5,876 items related to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak side handed over to the Czech side a database of transports of products under the conditional tax exemption regime initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3,319 items related to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech side compared the data on transports listed in the register of started transports in the Czech Republic with the records of transports completed in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak side compared data on transports of goods under the conditional tax exemption regime initiated in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">The comparison of data was complicated by the fact that the quantity of transported goods was not stated uniformly in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to unambiguously assign data on individual transports in both records, the accompanying documents were checked and breaches of the conditional tax exemption regime were not detected, nor were cases of tax evasion detected.</seg>
<seg id="217">Based on the findings of parallel controls, it can be stated that Member States can obtain valuable information from transport records to improve excise administration.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the movement and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152/2003 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council will allow electronic transmission of the accompanying document and more effective control of movement under suspension of excise duty within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="219">Communique</seg>
<seg id="220">This report has been prepared in Czech, English and Slovak.</seg>
<seg id="221">The report was signed by the Chairman of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office, Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="online-B">
<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of value added tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the ex - post control</seg>
<seg id="3">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are generally a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It is therefore self-evident that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) should focus on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example is value added tax (VAT) fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, an annual loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005, the participants of VI. the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">As part of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very good area for control cooperation, as it is the only tax harmonized within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also "SAO") and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, hereinafter also "BRH") carried out the first parallel VAT audit in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not limited to a single country but is widespread across the EU, close cooperation between SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to address this issue.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two SAIs therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a subsequent parallel inspection.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Inspection number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of inspection: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (follow-up inspection)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of the inspection:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the audit was to examine the procedure of financial authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for resolving selected cases of business transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany ("Germany"), and to examine the procedures of tax administrations of both countries in international cooperation .</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended for comparison with identified best practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period was the years 2006 to 2008, in the case of factual connections also the period preceding and following, until the end of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The subsequent audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">During previous parallel inspections, suspicious cases of intra-Community transactions were detected.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further verification.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations regarding VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up action was carried out to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspicious cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also focused, for example, on selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of receivables and the implementation of VAT audits of large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the audit of VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors came to the following audit findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from the previous inspection</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: The conditions for registration of payers should be harmonized across the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel audits, a comparison of VAT registration systems in the two countries revealed differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">Due to the different problems of different registration methods, both SAIs recommended harmonizing the conditions for payer registration within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation has been made at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal for an amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for an extension existing databases within the EU, including a database of VAT identification numbers.</seg>
<seg id="38">It also amended the common standards for the registration and registration of taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAIs expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as soon as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of this document, agreed by EU Member States in the framework of ECOFIN, no longer addresses this issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of ​​common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to consider this intention to be a relevant prevention tool in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports</seg>
<seg id="44">As part of international cooperation, the previous audit recommended that all EU countries introduce a one-month deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements, thus enabling a more timely verification of the values ​​of intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117 / EC amending Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion connected with intra-Community transactions shortens the period for which recapitulative statements are lodged EU, for one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, in Germany it was implemented from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit summary reports on a monthly basis was not introduced within the set deadline in accordance with the applicable EU regulations, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany in order to increase the reliability of VIES data and consider the interconnection of the two VAT return and recapitulative statements systems</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH's recommendations and set up a working group to examine possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">The work is still ongoing and the BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing successful risk management system criteria, components and approaches at EU level Based on the results of a previous audit, both SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system need to be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the perpetrators of fraud will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The audit found that our two Member States use different risk management systems, which have their strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO inspected the EUROCANET system, which enables the exchange of information within the EU, while the BRH focused on German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Subsequent control of selected cases of intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous audit, business transactions were examined jointly, where there were doubts about their execution or irregularities in the reporting of business transactions in tax returns or summary reports to taxpayers from both countries.</seg>
<seg id="58">Both SAIs selected nine cases for follow-up, which involved the intra-Community movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">The inspections carried out by the tax authorities of the countries concerned were not closed on the date of completion of our previous joint inspection.</seg>
<seg id="60">The follow-up audit verified that most tax proceedings in connection with the selected cases of commercial transactions between taxpayers from the Czech Republic and Germany were closed and that adequate measures were taken by the Czech or German tax authorities (eg additional VAT additional assessments or avoidance of input tax refunds). ).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Control of selected cases of risky intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intra-Community transactions executed by EU payers, which were included in the EUROCANET system, were selected for control.</seg>
<seg id="63">The EUROCANET system is a tool for detecting risky taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States' participation in this system is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in the EUROCANET system, while Germany has a passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active participant in a system if some Member States refuse active participation.</seg>
<seg id="67">Due to the fact that the German tax administration did not participate in the data exchange in the EUROCANET system, it was not possible to obtain any information on which suppliers with a German VAT ID were assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the audit, the SAO identified both cases of ordinary business transactions and cases of suspected involvement in carousel transactions or VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax administrators have limited possibilities to control risky transactions, especially with regard to so-called missing traders, while the mere physical examination of documents can hardly prove to the tax subject any fraudulent conduct.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation for tax administrations arises when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intra-Community carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be appropriate to ensure greater cooperation between customs and financial authorities in order to identify goods and irregularities in transport documentation and also to monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the final consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is hesitant to actively participate in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools are used to detect risky taxpayers, which have so far proved their worth to the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">There is a need to communicate and exchange experiences between EU Member States in this area.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council reached a political agreement on a draft regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with the use of EUROCANET should be the basis for the creation of this new network to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">In the field of international debt recovery assistance, all EU Member States follow the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the method of handling requests for international assistance in debt recovery in the Czech Republic and Germany is the same.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and the BRH compared the statistics submitted by both Member States to the European Commission for 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics did not match.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs find it useful to renegotiate statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent discrepancies.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without it, statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, SAIs agree that reliable statistics should include more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission to carry out an analysis on the basis of more detailed statistics to help Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In the view of both SAIs, this means helping Member States with a low recovery success rate to increase their debt recovery rate to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should be actively involved in this process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Control of large tax subjects</seg>
<seg id="90">The SAIs analyzed the legal situation regarding VAT control for large tax entities (hereinafter also "VDS") in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected information from tax administrations in the form of a questionnaire on areas that the SAIs consider essential for the management of this issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">It is clear from the responses received that the situation in the two countries is developing differently.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system in place to guide the selection of risk-prone cases, which is based on a large amount of relevant data (eg information from tax audits, data from balance sheets and profit and loss statements, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures effective management and analysis of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">In 2012, it is planned to establish a specialized financial office for the administration of VDS.</seg>
<seg id="96">A similar system does not yet exist in Germany, which makes it difficult to manage and analyze VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">So far, Germany has focused more on the selection of the individual cases in question, in particular on the basis of data from the VAT return and the recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="98">The analysis of these data is based on the various components of risk management that will be strengthened.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. The course of the control action</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 The course of the control action in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">The inspection was carried out in the period from May 2009 to February 2010 by Department II. - the state budget revenue department and the territorial departments IX. Pilsen, X. Ceske Budejovice, XIII. Brno and XV. Ostrava.</seg>
<seg id="102">The auditees were: the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also referred to as the "Czech Ministry of Finance") and 25 financial authorities (hereinafter also referred to as the "FI"): the Brno II, the Brno III, the Brno IV, the Břeclav, the Domažlice, the in Hodonín, FI in Hradec Králové, FI in Cheb, FI in Jablonec nad Nisou, FI in Karlovy Vary, FI in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FI in Kraslice, FI Ostrava I, FI Ostrava III, FI in Písek, FI in Pilsen, FI for Prague 1, FI for Prague 4, FI for Prague 8, FI in Rakovník, FI in Sokolov, FI in Tábor, FI in Vysoké Mýto, FI in Zlín and FI in Žamberk.</seg>
<seg id="103">The audit conclusion from this audit was approved by the Board of the Supreme Audit Office on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 The course of the inspection in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The audit was carried out between February 2009 and February 2010 by the indirect tax audit service and the staff of the designated regional audit offices in Berlin, Frankfurt am Main and Munich.</seg>
<seg id="106">After selecting a sample of cases, a number of Länder were informed of the mission of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="107">In addition to interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance, inspections took place in the following Länder: • Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hesse, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony.</seg>
<seg id="108">The tax files of the following tax offices were included: • Erlangen, Zentralfinanzamt München (Central Tax Office in Munich), Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord (Hamburg-North), Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg für Großunternehmen (Hamburg-VDS);</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, negotiations took place with the tax authorities of Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd (Halle-South) and with the financial directorates in Frankfurt am Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">A report on audit findings was submitted to the Federal Ministry of Finance in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two control institutions</seg>
<seg id="112">As part of the preparation of parallel inspections, a meeting of representatives of both inspection institutions took place in September 2008 to discuss and determine inspection topics.</seg>
<seg id="113">Subsequently, in December 2008, the top officials of the two SAIs signed an agreement on cooperation in carrying out parallel inspections.</seg>
<seg id="114">At a meeting in Bonn in June 2009, the audit teams informed each other of the initial results achieved during the preparation of the audit, discussed possible audit approaches and agreed on the way forward.</seg>
<seg id="115">The second meeting took place in Prague on 2-4 December 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The inspection teams exchanged the findings collected so far and agreed on a timetable for drawing up a joint report.</seg>
<seg id="117">In carrying out parallel audits, both SAIs decided to focus on: • follow-up of the implementation of the recommendations made in the previous report, • examination of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between Czech and German taxpayers that were not resolved during the previous parallel audit; transactions between taxpayers from the Czech Republic and Germany, which were classified as high-risk cases, • control of the procedure of tax administrations in the field of international assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables, • tax control of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">A report on the results of the parallel inspections was prepared during a working meeting in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Control of VAT administration in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Evaluation of recommendations from the previous inspection</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Evaluation of recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">The conditions for the registration of payers should be harmonized within the EU</seg>
<seg id="124">Based on the results of the previous audit, the SAO recommended an adjustment of the conditions for VAT registration and the introduction of a new rule for the cancellation of registration in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">The revised conditions should make it possible to reduce more effectively the risk of possible tax evasion in the collection of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="126">In this context, it was found that in some cases the tax authorities did not use the right to cancel VAT registration for taxpayers who did not fulfill their obligations under Act No. 235/2004 Coll., On Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as the “VAT Act”).</seg>
<seg id="127">The Czech Ministry of Finance has not yet proposed a change in the provision consisting in the introduction of the obligation of tax administrators to cancel VAT registration for taxpayers in the event of repeated failure to file a VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="128">According to the VAT Act, the tax administrator may cancel the registration of a taxpayer “ex offo” in cases where: a) the taxpayer has not performed without notification of the reason to the tax administrator for twelve consecutive months of performance, b) the taxpayer fails to fulfill his obligations under this Act; ) the taxpayer ceases to be a taxable person.</seg>
