<seg id="555">Both SAIs decided not to examine individual cases of VDS inspections, but focused on management issues in order to gain an overview of how tax administrations manage the issue of VAT inspections at VDS.</seg>
<seg id="556">In the form of a questionnaire, they gathered information from tax administrators on areas they consider essential for the management of this issue.</seg>
<seg id="557">• What statistical records and analyzes concerning the VAT control of VDS are available to the tax administration management?</seg>
<seg id="558">Especially:</seg>
<seg id="559">• Are there any statistics or records of the extent to which a distinction is made between the fight against VAT fraud and VAT control in general?</seg>
<seg id="560">Czech Republic: No, the ADIS system does not allow such a resolution in the current data version.</seg>
<seg id="561">Germany: The tax administration does not distinguish between controls designed to combat VAT fraud and general VAT controls.</seg>
<seg id="562">• Are there any statistics or records on the timeliness of VAT controls (in relation to the time period of the transactions audited)?</seg>
<seg id="563">Czech Republic: Records of the timeliness of inquiries with relevance for intra-Community acquisitions of goods for selected VAT payers are reported in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="564">In addition, the information recorded in the ADIS system also includes data on the type of query duration.</seg>
<seg id="565">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at federal level for tax auditors only contain information on the average time of the last audit (information on the year).</seg>
<seg id="566">This information does not provide an overview of selected control periods with respect to individual entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="567">VAT inspectors focus on the most recent tax assessment period; they also have the right to carry out VDS inspections.</seg>
<seg id="568">However, statistics produced at federal level for the VAT special control services do not provide information on the classification of taxable persons.</seg>
<seg id="569">• Are there any statistics or records on the nature of the additional tax revenue generated, broken down, for example, according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="570">i. a net increase in the tax liability (eg in cases where the taxable person has unduly applied a reduced VAT rate instead of the standard tax rate);</seg>
<seg id="571">ii. only a nominal increase in the tax liability (eg transfer of a fully qualified VAT case to another tax period);</seg>
<seg id="572">iii. additional collection of tax revenue (payment of additional tax due).</seg>
<seg id="573">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech Tax Administration monitors the number of tax audits performed, the volumes of additionally assessed tax broken down by type of tax, by the number of audited tax entities and by the number of audited tax periods.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (local investigations, reprimand proceedings) are monitored in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">Time data and amounts of additionally paid taxes are recorded as a separate task.</seg>
<seg id="577">General debt statistics are also kept broken down by type of tax, but not by declared tax or tax established by the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and for special VAT control departments do not distinguish between these criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">In addition, these differences are not distinguished by most of the tax administrations visited.</seg>
<seg id="580">• Are there areas of control that give rise to high additional revenues?</seg>
<seg id="581">Czech Republic: Yes, the tax administrator has the right to select taxpayers for verification on the basis of criteria that can be linked to selected indicators in special sections of ADIS.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">It follows that uniform statistics at the federal level for tax inspectors and for special VAT control departments do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, there is one coordinated approach by the finance ministers of the Länder and the federal government.</seg>
<seg id="585">In the ZAUBER database, tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder must enter the increased tax (VAT) liability imposed by them if they exceed a certain amount.</seg>
<seg id="586">In such a case, it must specify, for example, the nature of the assessed increase in the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="587">• What findings are most common?</seg>
<seg id="588">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="589">- VDS asserts an unjustified right to deduct input tax on supplies and services:</seg>
<seg id="590">• which have not been used to carry out any economic activity pursuant to Section 72 (1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="591">• which have been used for representation pursuant to Section 75 (3) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="592">• on the basis of tax documents that did not meet the requirements set out in Section 73 (1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="593">- VDS did not declare output VAT pursuant to Section 21 (1) of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: It was stated that there are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">It follows that uniform statistics at the federal level for tax inspectors and for special VAT control departments do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="596">Findings concerning VAT are not recorded separately by the Länder if they result from VDS tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, in the ZAUBER database, where tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder have to enter the increased tax (VAT) liability imposed by them if they exceed a certain amount, the Federal Central Tax Office is able to analyze this information.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the tax administration analyze areas of control that give rise to high “revenue” and draw implications for management?</seg>
<seg id="599">Czech Republic: Yes, for example, they are launching national audits focusing on risky commodities or the subject of economic activity.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Uniform statistics at the federal level for tax controllers and for the special VAT control departments do not provide data on audit areas from which high "revenues" flow.</seg>
<seg id="602">There are differing views on the analysis process as well as on case management in terms of relevance.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some regional tax authorities provide special information, but their use is at the discretion of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">The differences in the responses of the two Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects a lot of data from tax audits and data from financial statements - balance sheets and profit and loss statements.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to guide the selection of risk-prone cases.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, it is planned to establish a specialized financial office for the administration of VDS in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">It follows that it is more difficult to perform these tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places more emphasis on the selection of individual cases on the basis of data from submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">The risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to assess the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAIs agree that Member States should be able to ensure adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help reduce shortfalls in VAT revenues.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the revenue from VAT collection will increase and the level of risk detection for unreliable entrepreneurs will also improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of both SAIs on parallel inspections of the VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">The two SAIs became better acquainted with the systems in force in the following areas: • intra-Community transactions, • VAT risk management, in particular as regards the selection of risk-prone transactions, • assistance in recovering VAT receivables, and • VAT control for large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in the strategies for detecting cases of VAT fraud were revealed, as well as differences in the above-mentioned areas of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="621">Control findings were compared and best practices were identified.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to launch a debate on approaches and strategies within Member States, including at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of the two SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future control actions in the field of VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="624">6. Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="625">The report was prepared in Czech, English and German and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic and the President of the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof) of the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
